{"title_page": "Puerta de Tierra, San Juan", "text_new": "{{short description|Subbarrio of San Juan Antiguo, Puerto Rico}}\n[[File:Memorial in Puerta de Tierra, San Juan.jpg|thumb|Bike (memorial on tree) in Puerta de Tierra, San Juan]]\n'''Puerta de Tierra''' is a subbarrio occupying the eastern portion of the [[Barrios of Puerto Rico|barrio]] of [[San Juan Antiguo]] in the [[municipality]] of [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Puerto Rico]]. On October 15, 2019 it was added to the National Register of Historic Places, to be included with the [[Old San Juan Historic District]].\n\n==Setting==\n{{Historical populations|type=USA\n| 1899|5453\n| 1910|10836\n| 1920|15716\n| 1930|11936\n| 1935|13356\n| 1940|11480\n| 1950|9114\n| 1960|8075\n| 1970|6143\n| 1980|5522\n| 1990|5366\n| 2000|4135\n| 2010|2924\n|footnote=Populations of military and naval reserves are not included from 1899 through 1940.}}\n\n''Puerta de Tierra'' conforms the eastern portion of the Islet of San Juan and its connected to the mainland by bridges and a causeway. Puerta de Tierra is the site of many of [[Puerto Rico]]'s government buildings. With a [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]] population of 4,135 and a land area of 0.60 sq. miles (1.55&nbsp;km\u00b2), Puerta de Tierra is the largest and most populous subbarrio of San Juan Antiguo barrio.<ref name= \"2010 Census\">{{cite book|title=Puerto Rico: 2010 Population and housing unit counts| url = https://permanent.access.gpo.gov/gpo35934/cph-2-53.pdf|year=2010|page=76|publisher=U.S. Dept. of Commerce, Economics and Statistics Administration, U.S. Census Bureau}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Puerta de Tierra won an award from the [[International Union of Architects]], a non-governmental body based in Switzerland which represents the world's architects. Puerta de Tierra was awarded \"best public spaces\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elvocero.com/actualidad/otros/paseo-puerta-de-tierra-gana-premio-en-suiza/article_baa33702-3bbe-5d8e-b432-01075427115b.html|title=Paseo Puerta de Tierra gana premio en Suiza|first=Yaritza |last=Rivera Clemente|language=Spanish|website=El Vocero de Puerto Rico}}</ref>\n\n==National Register of Historic Places==\nOn October 15, 2019, Puerta de Tierra was officially added to the National Register of Historic Places. According to Puerto Rican newspaper {{lang|es|El Nuevo D\u00eda}}, Bibiana Hern\u00e1ndez had worked for decades to have Puerta de Tierra added to the US National Register of Historic Places (NRHP) and was overjoyed at the news. Many people such as artist and community spokesman, Jes\u00fas \u201cBubu\u201d Negr\u00f3n, have worked along with Arleen Pab\u00f3n-Charneco, a Puerto Rican architect and author of the NRHP nomination forms, to bring more visibility to the area. \n\nThe community expressed concerns saying the area was starting to experience gentrification. This designation now makes the entire [[Isleta de San Juan]] (San Juan Islet) a historic district, along with the [[Old San Juan Historic District]] (which is also on the small isle) and the designation should make it easier to prioritize its care with federal funds for these purposes. There were already thirteen structures in Puerta de Tierra on the NRHP, including El Falansterio, the Brambaugh school and the Jos\u00e9 Celso Barbosa school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/entretenimiento/cultura/nota/puertadetierraesdesignadacomodistritohistorico-2523920/|title=Puerta de Tierra es designada como distrito hist\u00f3rico [Puerta de Tierra is given historic district designation]|date=October 16, 2019|website=El Nuevo Dia|language=es}}</ref>\n\nThere is a phrase seen on murals around Puerta de Tierra that says {{lang|es|Aqu\u00ed vive gente}} (People live here) and the community has been planning to create a museum about Puerta de Tierra.<ref name=\"museum\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/entretenimiento/cultura/nota/lacomunidaddepuertadetierrainaugurasumuseodehistoriaycomunidadconunamuestraennuevayork-2496813/|title=La comunidad de Puerta de Tierra inaugura su Museo de Historia y Comunidad con una muestra en Nueva York|date=May 31, 2019|website=El Nuevo Dia|language=es}}</ref>\n\n==Attractions==\n\n=== Hotels and Beaches ===\n\n*[[Caribe Hilton Hotel]]\n*[[Normandie Hotel]]\n* Escambr\u00f3n Beach Club\n*[[Escambr\u00f3n Beach]]\n\n=== '''Parks and Recreation Sites''' ===\n\n*[[Luis Mu\u00f1oz Rivera Park]]\n*Third Millennium Park\n*[[Estadio Sixto Escobar|Sixto Escobar Stadium]]\n\n== Government Service Sites ==\n\n=== '''Federal Government of the United States''' ===\n\n* U.S. Food and Drug Administration Office\n*U.S. National Guard Office\n\n=== Commonwealth of Puerto Rico Legislative Branch ===\n\n* Capitol of Puerto Rico (Capitolio de Puerto Rico)\n\n=== '''Commonwealth of Puerto Rico Judicial Branch''' ===\n\n*[[Supreme Court of Puerto Rico]] (Tribunal Supremo de Puerto Rico)\n\n=== '''Autonomous Municipality of San Juan''' ===\n\n* Casa Cuna (US Navy Radio Station)\n**City Center for Children Protection\n*[https://sanjuanapp.wearecontactica.com/servicios/salud/ Dr. Quevedo B\u00e1ez Health Center]\n**Medical Primary Care and Emergency Room Services\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=\"170px\">\nSan Juan Antiguo Sub Barrios.jpg|Subbarrios of San Juan Antiguo\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Geography}}\n*[[San Juan Bay]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|San Juan/Puerta de Tierra|Puerta de Tierra}}\n\n{{coord|18|27|42|N|66|05|47|W|type:city_region:US-PR_source:GNIS-enwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Old San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Geography of San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Subbarrio of San Juan Antiguo, Puerto Rico}}\n[[File:Memorial in Puerta de Tierra, San Juan.jpg|thumb|Bike (memorial on tree) in Puerta de Tierra, San Juan]]\n'''Puerta de Tierra''' is a subbarrio occupying the eastern portion of the [[Barrios of Puerto Rico|barrio]] of [[San Juan Antiguo]] in the [[municipality]] of [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Puerto Rico]]. On October 15, 2019 it was added to the National Register of Historic Places, to be included with the [[Old San Juan Historic District]].\n\n==Setting==\n{{Historical populations|type=USA\n| 1899|5453\n| 1910|10836\n| 1920|15716\n| 1930|11936\n| 1935|13356\n| 1940|11480\n| 1950|9114\n| 1960|8075\n| 1970|6143\n| 1980|5522\n| 1990|5366\n| 2000|4135\n| 2010|2924\n|footnote=Populations of military and naval reserves are not included from 1899 through 1940.}}\n\n''Puerta de Tierra'' conforms the eastern portion of the Islet of San Juan and its connected to the mainland by bridges and a causeway. Puerta de Tierra is the site of many of [[Puerto Rico]]'s government buildings. With a [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]] population of 4,135 and a land area of 0.60 sq. miles (1.55&nbsp;km\u00b2), Puerta de Tierra is the largest and most populous subbarrio of San Juan Antiguo barrio.<ref name= \"2010 Census\">{{cite book|title=Puerto Rico: 2010 Population and housing unit counts| url = https://permanent.access.gpo.gov/gpo35934/cph-2-53.pdf|year=2010|page=76|publisher=U.S. Dept. of Commerce, Economics and Statistics Administration, U.S. Census Bureau}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Puerta de Tierra won an award from the [[International Union of Architects]], a non-governmental body based in Switzerland which represents the world's architects. Puerta de Tierra was awarded \"best public spaces\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elvocero.com/actualidad/otros/paseo-puerta-de-tierra-gana-premio-en-suiza/article_baa33702-3bbe-5d8e-b432-01075427115b.html|title=Paseo Puerta de Tierra gana premio en Suiza|first=Yaritza |last=Rivera Clemente|language=Spanish|website=El Vocero de Puerto Rico}}</ref>\n\n==National Register of Historic Places==\nOn October 15, 2019, Puerta de Tierra was officially added to the National Register of Historic Places. According to Puerto Rican newspaper {{lang|es|El Nuevo D\u00eda}}, Bibiana Hern\u00e1ndez had worked for decades to have Puerta de Tierra added to the US National Register of Historic Places (NRHP) and was overjoyed at the news. Many people such as artist and community spokesman, Jes\u00fas \u201cBubu\u201d Negr\u00f3n, have worked along with Arleen Pab\u00f3n-Charneco, a Puerto Rican architect and author of the NRHP nomination forms, to bring more visibility to the area. \n\nThe community expressed concerns saying the area was starting to experience gentrification. This designation now makes the entire [[Isleta de San Juan]] (San Juan Islet) a historic district, along with the [[Old San Juan Historic District]] (which is also on the small isle) and the designation should make it easier to prioritize its care with federal funds for these purposes. There were already thirteen structures in Puerta de Tierra on the NRHP, including El Falansterio, the Brambaugh school and the Jos\u00e9 Celso Barbosa school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/entretenimiento/cultura/nota/puertadetierraesdesignadacomodistritohistorico-2523920/|title=Puerta de Tierra es designada como distrito hist\u00f3rico [Puerta de Tierra is given historic district designation]|date=October 16, 2019|website=El Nuevo Dia|language=es}}</ref>\n\nThere is a phrase seen on murals around Puerta de Tierra that says {{lang|es|Aqu\u00ed vive gente}} (People live here) and the community has been planning to create a museum about Puerta de Tierra.<ref name=\"museum\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/entretenimiento/cultura/nota/lacomunidaddepuertadetierrainaugurasumuseodehistoriaycomunidadconunamuestraennuevayork-2496813/|title=La comunidad de Puerta de Tierra inaugura su Museo de Historia y Comunidad con una muestra en Nueva York|date=May 31, 2019|website=El Nuevo Dia|language=es}}</ref>\n\n==Attractions==\n\n=== Hotels and Beaches ===\n\n*[[Caribe Hilton Hotel]]\n*[[Normandie Hotel]]\n* Escambr\u00f3n Beach Club\n*[[Escambr\u00f3n Beach]]\n\n=== '''Parks and Recreation Sites''' ===\n\n*[[Luis Mu\u00f1oz Rivera Park]]\n*Third Millennium Park\n*[[Estadio Sixto Escobar|Sixto Escobar Stadium]]\n\n== Government Service Sites ==\n\n=== '''Federal government of the United States''' ===\n\n* U.S. Food and Drug Administration Office\n*U.S. National Guard Office\n\n=== Commonwealth of Puerto Rico Legislative Branch ===\n\n* Capitol of Puerto Rico (Capitolio de Puerto Rico)\n\n=== '''Commonwealth of Puerto Rico Judicial Branch''' ===\n\n*[[Supreme Court of Puerto Rico]] (Tribunal Supremo de Puerto Rico)\n\n=== '''Autonomous Municipality of San Juan''' ===\n\n* Casa Cuna (US Navy Radio Station)\n**Center for Children Protection\n*[https://sanjuanapp.wearecontactica.com/servicios/salud/ Dr. Quevedo B\u00e1ez Health Center]\n**Medical Primary Care and Emergency Room Services\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=\"170px\">\nSan Juan Antiguo Sub Barrios.jpg|Subbarrios of San Juan Antiguo\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Geography}}\n*[[San Juan Bay]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|San Juan/Puerta de Tierra|Puerta de Tierra}}\n\n{{coord|18|27|42|N|66|05|47|W|type:city_region:US-PR_source:GNIS-enwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Old San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Geography of San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n", "name_user": "El Corderito", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFederal government of the United States:Changed a capitalized letter.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Puerta_de_Tierra,_San_Juan"}
{"title_page": "Swedish Italians", "text_new": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Swedish Italians<br />''Svenskitalienare''<br/>''Italo-svedesi''\n| population = '''19,087'''<ref name=\"auto\">http://www.scb.se/Statistik/BE/BE0101/2011A01B/be0101_Fodelseland_och_ursprungsland.xls</ref>\n'''0.2%''' of the Swedish population (2012)<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n| popplace = [[Stockholm]] and [[Gothenburg]]\n| rels     = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| langs    = [[Swedish language|Swedish]], [[Italian language|Italian]]\n}}\n\n'''Swedish Italians''' ({{lang-sv|Svenskitalienare}}) are [[Sweden|Swedish]] citizens or residents of [[Italians|Italian]] ethnic, cultural and linguistic heritage or [[Identity (social science)|identity]].\nThere are approximately 8,126 people born in [[Italy]] living in Sweden today, as well as 10,961 people born in Sweden with at least one parent born in Italy.<ref>http://www.ccsenet.org/journal/index.php/ass/article/viewFile/8006/5998</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Notable Swedish Italians ==\n<gallery widths=95 heights=120 mode=nolines style=\"background:#fafafa; float:right; clear:right; width:308px; border:1px #aaa solid; line-height:120%\">\nFile:Marcus Birro 2010 cropped.jpg|[[Marcus Birro]]\nFile:Alexandra Zazzi 1.jpg|[[Alexandra Zazzi]]\nFile:Thomas Ravelli.jpg|[[Thomas Ravelli]]\nFile:Mauro Scocco 2012-10-05 001.jpg|[[Mauro Scocco]]\nFile:John_Guidetti_(2013,_cropped).jpg|[[John Guidetti]]\nFile:Sebastian_Ingrosso_playing_live_at_Ushuaia_Ibiza.jpeg|[[Sebastian Ingrosso]]\nFile:Alesso_playing_live_at_Ushuaia_Ibiza.jpeg|[[Alesso]]\nFile:Anna Maria Corazza Bildt,Sweden-MIP-Europaparlament-by-Leila-Paul-4.jpg|[[Anna Maria Corazza Bildt]]\nFile:Amelia Adamo.jpg|[[Amelia Adamo]]\nFile:Maria Taglioni Kriehuber.jpg|[[Marie Taglioni]]\nFile:Claudia Galli Cannes 2012 cropped.jpg|[[Claudia Galli]]\nFile:Veronica Maggio.jpg|[[Veronica Maggio]]\n</gallery>\n*[[Amelia Adamo]], editor-in-chief\n*[[Alesso]], DJ and producer\n*[[Anna Maria Corazza Bildt]], [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]\n*[[Marcus Birro]], poet, author and columnist\n*[[Peter Birro]], poet, author and columnist\n*[[Lydia Cappolicchio]], journalist and hostess\n*[[Johan De Farfalla]], musician\n*[[Staffan de Mistura]], UN and Arab League envoy to Syria\n*[[Thomas Di Leva]], singer-songwriter\n*[[Jonnie Fedel]], former football player\n*[[Helena Frith Powell]], columnist and author. (Italian mother)\n*[[Claudia Galli]], actress\n*[[Erik Gandini]], film director\n*[[John Guidetti]], football player\n*[[Sebastian Ingrosso]], DJ and producer\n*[[Pauline Kamusewu]], singer\n*[[Yvonne Lombard]], actress\n*[[Veronica Maggio]], singer\n*[[Angelique Magito]], opera singer in the 19th century\n*[[Michael Nyqvist]], actor\n*[[Hilda Petrini]], watchmaker in the 19th century\n*[[Andreas Ravelli]], former footballer\n*[[Thomas Ravelli]], former footballer\n*[[Paolo Roberto]], actor and former boxer\n*[[Mauro Scocco]], singer\n*[[Marie Taglioni]], ballet dancer in the 19th century\n*[[Roberto Vacchi]], former cyclist\n*[[Andreas Vinciguerra]], former tennis player\n*[[Alexandra Zazzi]], chef\n*[[Oscar Zia]], singer\n*[[Gennaro Selvaggi]], surgeon\n\n==See also==\n* [[Italian diaspora]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Italian diaspora}}\n{{Immigration to Sweden}}\n\n[[Category:Immigration to Sweden|Italian]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Sweden|Italian]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of Italian descent| ]]\n[[Category:Italian diaspora by country|Sweden]]\n[[Category:Italian diaspora in Europe|Sweden]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Swedish Italians<br />''Svenskitalienare''<br/>''Italo-svedesi''\n| population = '''19,087'''<ref name=\"auto\">http://www.scb.se/Statistik/BE/BE0101/2011A01B/be0101_Fodelseland_och_ursprungsland.xls</ref>\n'''0.2%''' of the Swedish population (2012)<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n| popplace = [[Stockholm]] and [[Gothenburg]]\n| rels     = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| langs    = [[Swedish language|Swedish]], [[Italian language|Italian]]\n}}\n\n'''Swedish Italians''' ({{lang-sv|Svenskitalienare}}) are [[Sweden|Swedish]] citizens or residents of [[Italians|Italian]] ethnic, cultural and linguistic heritage or [[Identity (social science)|identity]].\nThere are approximately 8,126 people born in [[Italy]] living in Sweden today, as well as 10,961 people born in Sweden with at least one parent born in Italy.<ref>http://www.ccsenet.org/journal/index.php/ass/article/viewFile/8006/5998</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Notable Swedish Italians ==\n<gallery widths=95 heights=120 mode=nolines style=\"background:#fafafa; float:right; clear:right; width:308px; border:1px #aaa solid; line-height:120%\">\nFile:Marcus Birro 2010 cropped.jpg|[[Marcus Birro]]\nFile:Alexandra Zazzi 1.jpg|[[Alexandra Zazzi]]\nFile:Thomas Ravelli.jpg|[[Thomas Ravelli]]\nFile:Mauro Scocco 2012-10-05 001.jpg|[[Mauro Scocco]]\nFile:John_Guidetti_(2013,_cropped).jpg|[[John Guidetti]]\nFile:Sebastian_Ingrosso_playing_live_at_Ushuaia_Ibiza.jpeg|[[Sebastian Ingrosso]]\nFile:Alesso_playing_live_at_Ushuaia_Ibiza.jpeg|[[Alesso]]\nFile:Anna Maria Corazza Bildt,Sweden-MIP-Europaparlament-by-Leila-Paul-4.jpg|[[Anna Maria Corazza Bildt]]\nFile:Amelia Adamo.jpg|[[Amelia Adamo]]\nFile:Maria Taglioni Kriehuber.jpg|[[Marie Taglioni]]\nFile:Claudia Galli Cannes 2012 cropped.jpg|[[Claudia Galli]]\nFile:Veronica Maggio.jpg|[[Veronica Maggio]]\n</gallery>\n*[[Amelia Adamo]], editor-in-chief\n*[[Alesso]], DJ and producer\n*Baroness [[Anna Maria Corazza Bildt]], MEP\n*[[Marcus Birro]], poet, author and columnist\n*[[Peter Birro]], poet, author and columnist\n*[[Lydia Cappolicchio]], journalist and hostess\n*[[Johan De Farfalla]], musician\n*[[Staffan de Mistura]], UN and Arab League envoy to Syria\n*[[Thomas Di Leva]], singer-songwriter\n*[[Jonnie Fedel]], former football player\n*[[Helena Frith Powell]], columnist and author. (Italian mother)\n*[[Claudia Galli]], actress\n*[[Erik Gandini]], film director\n*[[John Guidetti]], football player\n*[[Sebastian