{"title_page": "1986 Chicago Bears season", "text_new": "{{Infobox NFL season\n| team = Chicago Bears\n| logo = Chicago Bears logo.svg\n| year = 1986\n| record = 14\u20132\n| division_place = 1st [[NFC Central]]\n| coach = [[Mike Ditka]]<br>''(5th season)''\n| general manager = [[Jerry Vainisi]]<br>''(Since 1983)''\n| owner = [[Virginia Halas McCaskey|The McCaskey Family]]<br>''(Family control since 1921;  Virginia McCaskey since 1983)''\n| stadium = [[Soldier Field]]\n| pro bowlers = {{Collapsible list\n |title = 7<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1986/probowl.htm |title=1986 NFL Pro Bowlers |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com}}</ref>\n |1 = RB [[Walter Payton]]\n |2 = LT [[Jim Covert|Jimbo Covert]]\n |3 = C [[Jay Hilgenberg]]\n |4 = DT [[Steve McMichael]]\n |5 = LB [[Wilber Marshall]]\n |6 = MLB [[Mike Singletary]]\n |7 = SS [[Dave Duerson]]\n }}\n| AP All-pros =  {{Collapsible list\n |title = 11<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1986/allpro.htm |title=1986 NFL All-Pros |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com}}</ref>\n |1 = WR [[Dennis Gentry]]\n |2 = RB [[Walter Payton]]\n |3 = RB [[Neal Anderson]]\n |4 = LT [[Jim Covert|Jimbo Covert]]\n |5 = C [[Jay Hilgenberg]]\n |6 = DE [[Dan Hampton]]\n |7 = DT [[Steve McMichael]]\n |8 = LB [[Wilber Marshall]]\n |9 = MLB [[Mike Singletary]]\n |10 = CB [[Mike Richardson (American football, born 1961)|Mike Richardson]]\n |11 = SS [[Dave Duerson]]\n }}\n| playoffs = Lost [[1986\u201387 NFL playoffs|Divisional Playoffs]] ([[1986 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]]) 27\u201313\n| shortnavlink = Bears seasons\n}}\nThe '''[[1986 NFL season|1986]] [[Chicago Bears]] season''' was their 67th [[Regular Season (NFL)|regular season]] and 17th [[NFL playoffs|post-season]] completed in the [[National Football League]]. The Bears entered the season looking to repeat as [[Super Bowl XX|Super Bowl champions]], as they had won in [[1985 Chicago Bears season|1985]]. Chicago managed to finish 14\u20132, one game off of their 1985 record of 15\u20131. Although the Bears had an equal 14-2 record as the [[1986 New York Giants|New York Giants]] for the league\u2019s best record, the Giants were seeded number one in the NFC for the playoffs due to the Giants having a better conference record (11-1) than that of the Bears (10-2).\n\nAfter winning the [[Super Bowl XX|championship]] in [[1985 Chicago Bears season|1985]], the Bears seemed like a dynasty in the making. However, quarterback [[Jim McMahon]] showed up to training camp 25 pounds overweight&nbsp;\u2013 the product of the post-Super Bowl partying he\u2019d partaken in. Nonetheless, he was once again named as the starter. Injuries, however, derailed his season. McMahon played in only six of the team\u2019s first 12 games.\n\nAided by a strong [[offensive line]], the Bears were once again led on offense by [[Walter Payton]]. Payton remained his usual stellar self, posting his 10th and final 1,000-yard season. With McMahon\u2019s poor play, as well as the equally poor play of backups [[Mike Tomczak]], [[Steve Fuller (football player)|Steve Fuller]] and [[Doug Flutie]], Payton was the sole spark on offense, which ranked 13th in the [[National Football League|NFL]].\n\nAs had been the case the year before, the Bears were once again led by their explosive defense. Any shortcomings on the offensive side of the ball were more than made up for on the defensive side. They once again were ranked #1 in the NFL. The Bears\u2019 defense became the third defense in the history of the NFL to lead the league in fewest points allowed and fewest total yards allowed for two consecutive seasons.<ref>''The Best Show in Football: The 1946\u20131955 Cleveland Browns'', p. 294, Andy Piascik, Taylor Trade Publishing, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-58979-360-6}}</ref> The Bears\u2019 187 points allowed is the fewest surrendered by any team in the 1980s (other than the [[1982 NFL strike|strike-shortened]] [[1982 NFL season|1982 season]]) \u2013 even fewer than the 198 points the Bears allowed in their historic 1985 season.\n\nHowever, the Bears were not able to recapture their magic from the season before and were bounced from the playoffs in their first game by [[1986 Washington Redskins season|the Washington Redskins]].\n\n==1986 NFL Draft==\n\n{{main article|1986 NFL Draft}}\n{{NFL team draft start\n|teamname=Chicago Bears\n|year=1986\n}}\n{{NFL team draft entry\n | round = [[List of Chicago Bears first-round draft picks|1]]\n | pick         = 27\n | player         = [[Neal Anderson]]\n | position      = [[Running back]]\n | college   = [[Florida Gators football|Florida]]\n | notes = \n | maderoster     = yes\n | hof = \n | probowl    = yes\n}}\n{{NFL team draft entry\n | round = 2\n | pick         = 55\n | player         = [[Vestee Jackson]]\n | position      = [[Cornerback]]\n | college   = [[Washington Huskies football|Washington]]\n | notes = \n | maderoster     = yes\n | hof = \n}}\n{{NFL team draft entry\n | round = 3\n | pick         = 82\n | player         = [[David Williams (wide receiver)|David Williams]]\n | position      = [[Wide receiver]]\n | college   = [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|Illinois]]\n | notes = \n | maderoster     = no\n | hof = \n}}\n{{NFL team draft entry\n | round = 4\n | pick         = 110\n | player         = Paul Blair\n | position      = [[Tackle (gridiron football position)|Tackle]]\n | college   = [[Oklahoma State Cowboys football|Oklahoma State]]\n | notes = \n | maderoster     = yes\n | hof = \n}}\n{{NFL team draft entry\n | round = 5\n | pick         = 138\n | player         = [[Lew Barnes]]\n | position      = [[Wide receiver]]\n | college   = [[University of Oregon|Oregon]]\n | notes = \n | maderoster     = yes\n | hof = \n}}\n{{NFL team draft entry\n | round = 6\n | pick         = 166\n | player         = [[Jeff Powell (American football)|Jeff Powell]]\n | position      = [[Running back]]\n | college   = [[Tennessee Volunteers foot