ox start\n|Title=Chicago Bears at Dallas Cowboys\n|Visitor='''Bears'''\n|V1=7 |V2=14 |V3=3 |V4=0\n|Host=Cowboys\n|H1=0 |H2=0 |H3=0 |H4=10\n|Date=Sunday, December 21\n|Location=[[Texas Stadium]], [[Irving, Texas]]\n|StartTime=3:00 p.m.\n|TimeZone=CST\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=\n|Weather={{convert|47|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|1}}, wind {{convert|8|mph|km/h knots}}\n|Referee=[[Fred Wyant]]\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n*'''Source:''' [https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/198612210dal.htm Pro-Football-Reference.com]\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |FirstEntry= yes|Quarter=1 |Time= |Team=Bears |Event=[[Walter Payton]] 1-yard run ([[Kevin Butler (American football)|Kevin Butler]] kick) |Score=Bears 7\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=2 |Time= |Team=Bears |Event=[[Neal Anderson]] 58-yard pass from [[Doug Flutie]] (Kevin Butler kick) |Score=Bears 14\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=2 |Time= |Team=Bears |Event=[[Willie Gault]] 33-yard pass from Doug Flutie (Kevin Butler kick) |Score= Bears 21\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=3 |Time= |Team=Bears |Event=Kevin Butler 31-yard field goal |Score= Bears 24\u20130}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter= 4|Time= |Team=Cowboys |Event= [[Rafael Septi\u00e9n]] 50-yard field goal|Score= Bears 24\u20133}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter= 4|Time= |Team=Cowboys |Event=[[Mike Renfro]] 11-yard pass from [[Steve Pelluer]] (Rafael Septien kick) |Score=Bears 24\u201310 |LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Playoffs==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Week\n! Date\n! Opponent\n! Result\n! Attendance\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| Divisional\n| January 3, 1987\n| [[1986 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]]\n| L 27\u201313\n| <center>65,141</center>\n|}\n\n===Game summary===\n{{Americanfootballbox\n |titlestyle={{NFLPrimaryStyle|Chicago Bears|border=2}};text-align:center;\n |state=autocollapse\n |title=NFC Divisional Playoff: Washington Redskins at Chicago Bears&nbsp;\u2013 Game summary\n |date= January 3, 1987\n |time=4:00 p.m. EDT\n |road='''Redskins'''\n |R1=7|R2=0|R3=7|R4=13|RT=27\n |home=Bears|H1=0|H2=13|H3=0|H4=0|HT=13\n |stadium=[[Soldier Field]], [[Chicago]]\n |weather={{convert|33|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|1}}, wind {{convert|7|mph|km/h knots}}\n|reference= Boxscore [https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/198701030chi.htm]\n |scoring=\n'''First quarter'''\n*WAS \u2013 [[Art Monk]] 28 yard pass from [[Jay Schroeder]] (Jess Atkinson kick) '''''Redskins 7-0'''''\n'''Second quarter'''\n*CHI \u2013 Willie Gault 50 yard pass from [[Doug Flutie]] ([[Kevin Butler (American football)|Kevin Butler]] kick) '''''Tie 7-7'''''\n*CHI \u2013 [[Kevin Butler (American football)|Kevin Butler]] 23 yard field goal. '''''Bears 10-7'''''\n*CHI \u2013 [[Kevin Butler (American football)|Kevin Butler]] 41 yard field goal. '''''Bears 13-7'''''\n'''Third quarter'''\n*WAS \u2013 [[Art Monk]] 23 yard pass from [[Jay Schroeder]] (Jess Atkinson kick) '''''Redskins 14-13'''''\n'''Fourth quarter'''\n*WAS \u2013 George Rogers 1 yard run (Jess Atkinson kick) '''''Redskins 21-13'''''\n*WAS \u2013 Jessie Atkinson 35 yard field goal. '''''Redskins 24-13'''''\n*WAS \u2013 Jessie Atkinson 25 yard field goal. '''''Redskins 27-13'''''\n|stats=\n'''Redskins'''\n*Jay Schroeder. 15\u201332, 185 yards, 2 TD, 1 Int\n*Art Monk. 5 rec, 81 yards, 2 TD\n*\n'''Bears'''\n*Doug Flutie. 11\u201331, 134 yards, 1 TD, 2 Int\n*Walter Payton. 14 rush, 38 yards. \n*\n'''Turnovers''': \n*Redskins \u2013 1\n*Bears \u2013 4\n}}\nThe 1986 Bears earned a first round playoff bye, but in their opening playoff game, they were upset [[Soldier Field|at home]] by the [[Washington Redskins]]. A holding penalty and a missed field goal by [[Kevin Butler (American football)|Kevin Butler]] frustrated the Bears in the first quarter. They still, however, managed to take a 13\u20137 lead into halftime. But their usually stout defense fell apart in the second half, allowing the Redskins to score 20 unanswered points.\n\n\u201cMaybe my dreams didn\u2019t come true\u201c, said Chicago Coach [[Mike Ditka]]. \u201cThe defense has to play outstanding and today they were just not up to the way the Redskins were playing.\u201d\n\nDespite injuries to Redskins [[offensive linemen]] [[Joe Jacoby]] and [[Russ Grimm]], the Washington offensive line was able to pick up the Bears patented blitzes. Washington quarterback [[Jay Schroeder]] was sacked only twice. He was also able to use the blitzes to his advantage, completing passes while being chased out of the pocket.\n\nTrailing 14\u201313 in the 4th quarter, the Bears good fortune ran out, when the usually dependable Payton lost a fumble, which led to an 83-yard touchdown drive by the Redskins. The long drive perpetrated against the NFL\u2019s best defense seemed to take the wind out of the Bears' sails. A few minutes later, the Bears muffed a punt return which set up an easy field goal for the Redskins. The Bears lost 27\u201313.\n\n==Standings==\n{{1986 NFC Central standings}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.bearshistory.com/seasons/1986chicagobears.aspx 1986 Chicago Bears Season at www.bearshistory.com]\n\n{{Chicago Bears}}\n{{Chicago Bears seasons}}\n{{1986 NFL season by team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1986 Chicago Bears Season}}\n[[Category:NFC Central championship seasons]]\n[[Category:1986 National Football League season by team|Chicago Bears]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bears seasons]]\n[[Category:1986 in sports in Illinois|Chicago]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NFL season\n| team = Chicago Bears\n| logo = Chicago Bears logo.svg\n| year = 1986\n| record = 14\u20132\n| division_place = 1st [[NFC Central]]\n| coach = [[Mike Ditka]]<br>''(5th season)''\n| general manager = [[Jerry Vainisi]]<br>''(Since 1983)''\n| owner = [[Virginia Halas McCaskey|The McCaskey Family]]<br>''(Family control since 1921;  Virginia McCaskey since 1983)''\n| stadium = [[Soldier Field]]\n| pro bowlers = {{Collapsible list\n |title = 7<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1986/probowl.htm |title=1986 NFL Pro Bowlers |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com}}</ref>\n |1 = RB [[Walter Payton]]\n |2 = LT [[Jim Covert|Jimbo Covert]]\n |3 = C [[Jay Hilgenberg]]\n |4 = DT [[Steve McMichael]]\n |5 = LB [[Wilber Marshall]]\n |6 = MLB [[Mike Singletary]]\n |7 = SS [[Dave Duerson]]\n }}\n| AP All-pros =  {{Collapsible list\n |title = 11<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1986/allpro.htm |title=1986 NFL All-Pros |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com}}</ref>\n |1 = WR [[Dennis Gentry]]\n |2 = RB [[Walter Payton]]\n |3 = RB [[Neal Anderson]]\n |4 = LT [[Jim Covert|Jimbo Covert]]\n |5 = C [[Jay Hilgenberg]]\n |6 = DE [[Dan Hampton]]\n |7 = DT [[Steve McMichael]]\n |8 = LB [[Wilber Marshall]]\n |9 = MLB [[Mike Singletary]]\n |10 = CB [[Mike Richardson (American football, born 1961)|Mike Richardson]]\n |11 = SS [[Dave Duerson]]\n }}\n| playoffs = Lost [[1986\u201387 NFL playoffs|Divisional Playoffs]] ([[1986 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]]) 27\u201313\n| shortnavlink = Bears seasons\n}}\nThe '''[[1986 NFL season|1986]] [[Chicago Bears]] season''' was their 67th [[Regular Season (NFL)|regular season]] and 17th [[NFL playoffs|post-season]] completed in the [[National Football League]]. The Bears entered the season looking to repeat as [[Super Bowl XX|Super Bowl champions]], as they had won in [[1985 Chicago Bears season|1985]]. Chicago managed to finish 14\u20132, one game off of their 1985 record of 15\u20131. Although the Bears had an equal 14-2 record as the [[1986 New York Giants|the New York Giants]] for the league\u2019s best record, the Giants were seeded number one in the NFC for the playoffs due to the Giants having a better conference record (11-1) than that of the Bears (10-2).\n\nAfter winning the [[Super Bowl XX|championship]] in [[1985 Chicago Bears season|1985]], the Bears seemed like a dynasty in the making. However, quarterback [[Jim McMahon]] showed up to training camp 25 pounds overweight&nbsp;\u2013 the product of the post-Super Bowl partying he\u2019d partaken in. Nonetheless, he was once again named as the starter. Injuries, however, derailed his season. McMahon played in only six of the team\u2019s first 12 games.\n\nAided by a strong [[offensive line]], the Bears were once again led on offense by [[Walter Payton]]. Payton remained his usual stellar self, posting his 10th and final 1,000-yard season. With McMahon\u2019s poor play, as well as the equally poor play of backups [[Mike Tomczak]], [[Steve Fuller (football player)|Steve Fuller]] and [[Doug Flutie]], Payton was the sole spark on offense, which ranked 13th in the [[National Football League|NFL]].\n\nAs had been the case the year before, the Bears were once again led by their explosive defense. Any shortcomings on the offensive side of the ball were more than made up for on the defensive side. They once again were ranked #1 in the NFL. The Bears\u2019 defense became the third defense in the history of the NFL to lead the league in fewest points allowed and fewest total yards allowed for two consecutive seasons.<ref>''The Best Show in Football: The 1946\u20131955 Cleveland Browns'', p. 294, Andy Piascik, Taylor Trade Publishing, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-58979-360-6}}</ref> The Bears\u2019 187 points allowed is the fewest surrendered by any team in the 1980s (other than the [[1982 NFL strike|strike-shortened]] [[1982 NFL season|1982 season]]) \u2013 even fewer than the 198 points the Bears allowed in their historic 1985 season.\n\nHowever, the Bears were not able to recapture their magic from the season before and were bounced from the playoffs in their first game by [[1986 Washington Redskins season|the Washington Redskins]].\n\n==1986 NFL Draft==\n\n{{main article|1986 NFL Draft}}\n{{NFL team draft start\n|teamname=Chicago Bears\n|year=1986\n}}\n{{NFL team draft entry\n | round = [