 and East London]\n* [http://www.gypsy-traveller.org/ Friends, Families and Travellers. Advice and Information for Gypsies and Travellers] {{link note|note=UK-based charity}}\n* [http://cnnphotos.blogs.cnn.com/2012/10/24/irelands-biggest-minority-group/?hpt=hp_c2 \"Ireland's biggest minority group\"] {{link note|note=''CNN'' photo blog}}\n* [http://politico.ie/society/when-i-do-taboo When is 'I do' taboo?] {{link note|note=About carrier testing to determine the risks of genetic disorders in Irish Traveller cousin marriages}}\n* [http://www.tvgcork.ie/ 'The website of Cork Traveller Visibility Group Ltd'] {{link note|note=A community development organisation which works to support Travellers in their day to day lives so they can participate in Irish society as equals.}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/Spring-Lane-Site-Solidarity-Group-445847145542831/ 'The Facebook page of Spring Lane Site Solidarity Group'] {{link note|note=A group of professionals and community activists whose aim is to highlight the humanitarian crisis on Spring Lane halting site & advocate for change}}\n\n{{Irish Travellers}}\n{{Celtic nations}}\n{{British Isles}}\n{{EuropeansinUK}}\n{{UK census ethnic groups}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in the United States]]\n[[Category:Irish culture]]\n[[Category:Irish diaspora]]\n[[Category:Irish Travellers| ]]\n[[Category:Nomadic groups in Eurasia]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Census 2001]]\n", "name_user": "Smjg", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eViolence and crime:sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_Travellers"}
{"title_page": "Russell Okung", "text_new": "{{short description|American football offensive tackle}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Russell Okung\n|image= Russell Okung 2016.jpg\n|image_size=\n|alt=\n|caption= Okung with the Denver Broncos in 2016\n|current_team =Carolina Panthers\n|number=\n|position=[[Offensive tackle]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1988|10|7|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Houston, Texas]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 5\n|weight_lbs = 310\n|high_school = [[George Bush High School|George Bush]]<br>([[Richmond, Texas]])\n|college=[[Oklahoma State Cowboys football|Wakanda Tech ]]\n|draftyear=2010\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=6\n|pastteams=\n* [[Seattle Seahawks]] ({{NFL Year|2010}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2015}})\n* [[Denver Broncos]] ({{NFL Year|2016}})\n* [[Los Angeles Chargers]] ({{NFL Year|2017}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2019}})\n* [[Carolina Panthers]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n|status=Active\n|highlights=\n* [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XLVIII|XLVIII]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2013 Pro Bowl|2012]], [[2018 Pro Bowl|2017]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[All-American]] ([[2008 College Football All-America Team|2008]], [[2009 College Football All-America Team|2009]])\n* [[Touchdown Club of Columbus#The Jim Parker Trophy|Jim Parker Trophy]] (2009)\n* [[Big 12 Offensive Lineman of the Year]] (2009)\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-Big 12 (2008, 2009)\n* Dick Bogert Award (2006)\n|statweek=\n|statseason=2019\n|statlabel1=Games played\n|statvalue1=124\n|statlabel2=Games started\n|statvalue2=124\n|nflnew=russellokung/497032\n}}\n\n'''Russell Okung''' ({{IPAc-en|o\u028a|\u02c8|k|\u028a|\u014b}} {{respell|oh|KUUNG|'}}; born October 7, 1988<ref>[http://www.russellokung.com/about/ About Russell Okung]</ref>) is an [[American football]] [[offensive tackle]] for the [[Carolina Panthers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] for [[Oklahoma State University]], and was twice recognized as an [[All-American]]. He was drafted by the [[Seattle Seahawks]] with the sixth overall pick in the [[2010 NFL Draft]], and has also played for the [[Denver Broncos]] and the [[Los Angeles Chargers]].\n\n==Early years==\nOkung was born in [[Houston, Texas]].  He attended [[George Bush High School]] in Fort Bend, where he was a first-team All-Greater Houston and first-team all-district selection.  He was also one of the state's top performers in the [[discus throw]] (PR of 47.50 meters). Considered a three-star prospect by ''[[Rivals.com]]'',<ref>{{citation |title=Russell Okung Profile |url=https://footballrecruiting.rivals.com/viewprospect.asp?pr_key=40016&sport=1 |work=Rivals.com |accessdate= }}</ref> Okung was listed as the No. 33 offensive tackle prospect in the class of 2006.<ref>{{Citation |url=https://footballrecruiting.rivals.com/viewrank.asp?ra_key=1150 |title=Offensive tackles 2006 |work=Rivals.com |date=January 30, 2006 }}.</ref>  At {{convert|250|lb|kg|0}} coming out of high school, he did not possess the prototypical tackle bulk.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://insider.espn.go.com/ncf/recruiting/tracker/player?recruitId=35168 |work=ESPN |title=Russell Okung Recruiting Profile |date=February 1, 2006 }}.</ref>  Okung was recruited by a number of major schools, including [[University of Oklahoma|Oklahoma]], [[Louisiana State University|LSU]], and [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln|Nebraska]]. He committed to Oklahoma State in January 2006.\n\n==College career==\nOkung attended [[Oklahoma State University]], where he played for coach [[Mike Gundy]]'s [[Oklahoma State Cowboys football]] team from 2006 to 2009.  As a [[true freshman]], he moved into the starting lineup for the first time against [[University of Kansas|Kansas]] and held the position of right tackle for the rest of the season (eight straight starts). He ended the season by being voted as a member of All-Big 12 freshman team (by ''[[The Sporting News]]'') and was named the Dick Bogert Award winner as Oklahoma State's top freshman.\n\nIn his sophomore season, he started all thirteen games, having been moved permanently to left tackle. The Cowboys\u2019 offensive line gave up just five sacks in eight Big 12 games to lead the league in that category. Okung earned honorable mention all-Big 12 honors (by coaches). He was also named to the ''Rivals.com'' all-bowl team after holding Indiana's [[Greg Middleton]], the NCAA's sack leader, without a tackle in the [[2007 Insight Bowl]] victory.<ref>{{Citation |work=Rivals.com |date=January 9, 2008 |title=Coming up big in the biggest games |url=http://collegefootball.rivals.com/content.asp?SID=1144&CID=759478 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080520153800/http://collegefootball.rivals.com/content.asp?SID=1144&CID=759478 |archivedate=May 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Russel Okung Broncos Practice 2016 - 2.jpg|thumb|left]]\nAs a junior, Okung led Oklahoma State with 71 knockdown blocks, and was named a first-team all-conference selection by the coaches.  He also was named to ''[[Pro Football Weekly]]''\u2032s 2008 All-America team.<ref>{{Citation |first=Nolan |last=Nawrocki |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Pro Football Weekly's 2008 All-America team |url=http://www.profootballweekly.com/PFW/College+Football/College+Football+Extras/2008/allamerica.htm |work=Pro Football Weekly |publisher= |date=December 22, 2008 |accessdate= }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  Okung currently has started 34 straight games for the longest active streak on the team.\n\nIn 2009, Okung was listed at No. 1 on ''[[Rivals.com]]\u2032s'' preseason offensive tackle power ranking.<ref>{{Citation |last=Buchanan |first=Olin |last2=Dienhart |first2=Tom |last3=Fox |first3=David |last4=Huguenin |first4=Mike |last5=Megargee |first5=Steve |date=August 22, 2009 |title=Preseason offensive tackle power rankings |work=Rivals.com |url=http://rivals100.rivals.com/content.asp?cid=978914 }}</ref> He was also named to the 2009 [[Outland Trophy]] watch list.<ref name=\"FWAA Outland\">{{Citation |last=Richardson |first=Steve |date=August 11, 2009 |title=2009 Outland Trophy Watch List Announced |publisher=[[Football Writers Association of America]] |url=http://www.sportswriters.net/fwaa/news/2009/outland090811.html }}</ref> On October 14, 2009, Okung was named one of twelve semifinalists\u2014and the only offensive lineman\u2014for the [[Lombardi Award]].<ref>{{Citation |date=October 14, 2009 |title=Okung Named Lombardi Semi-Finalist |work=OK State Athletics |url=http://www.okstate.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/101409aaa.html }}</ref>\n\nIn a game against [[2009 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]] on October 10, Okung held then-NCAA sack leader, [[Von Miller]], without a quarterback sack. That effort was the second time during his career he has not allowed a sack against the nation's leader at the time. Against [[2009 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]] on October 31, Okung held the Longhorn pass rush, including All-American candidate [[Sergio Kindle]], without a quarterback sack. According to ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'s'' Tony Pauline, that performance \"has solidified his projection as the top senior tackle\" in the 2010 NFL Draft.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/football/nfl/11/02/risers/ |title=Sam Bradford, 2010 NFL Draft, rising, sliding prospects |work=Sports Illustrated |last=Pauline |first=Tony |date=November 2, 2009 }}</ref> On November 24, 2009, Okung was named one of three finalists for the 2009 [[Outland Trophy]], alongside [[Mike Iupati]] and [[Ndamukong Suh]].<ref name=\"GriffinESPNOutland\">{{Citation |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/ncfnation/post/_/id/14004/okung-suh-named-outland-trophy-finalists |title=Okung, Suh named Outland Trophy finalists |last=Griffin |first=Tom |work=ESPN |date=November 24, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOn December 1, 2009, Okung was named Big 12 Offensive Lineman of the Year in a vote of the league's coaches.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.okstate.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/120109aaa.html |title=Okung Named Big 12 O-Lineman of the Year |work=Oklahoma State Athletics |date=December 1, 2009 }}</ref>  He was also recognized as a unanimous first-team [[2009 College Football All-America Team|2009 All-American]].<ref>{{Citation |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/big12/post/_/id/8482/seven-big-12-players-make-consensus-all-america-list |title=Seven Big 12 players make All-America list |last=Griffin |first=Tim |publisher=ESPN |date=December 17, 2009 }}</ref> Despite tweaking his knee in practice earlier that week, Okung played in the [[2010 Cotton Bowl Classic]] to end his career at Oklahoma State with a streak of 47 straight starts.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.newsok.com/osus-russell-okung-likely-to-play-in-cotton-bowl/article/3428640 |newspaper=The Oklahoman |title=OSU's Russell Okung likely to play in Cotton Bowl |date=December 31, 2009 |last=Chatmon |first=Brandon |last2=Helsley |first2=John }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=300020145 |title=McCluster's 182 yards, two TDs propel Ole Miss to Cotton Bowl victory |work=ESPN |date=January 2, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n[[File:Russell Okung.jpg|thumb|150px|Okung with the Seattle Seahawks in 2013]]\n\nOkung was considered one of the best offensive tackles available in the [[2010 NFL Draft]],<ref name=\"PriscoCBS\">{{Citation |first=Pete |last=Prisco |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Prisco's 2010 draft preview: QB will land No. 1 spot |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/story/11684517 |work=CBSSports.com |publisher= |date=April 27, 2009 |accessdate= }}</ref><ref name=\"CooneyUSAToday\">{{Citation |first=Frank |last=Cooney |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Who's next? Looking ahead to the best of the 2010 draft class |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/2009-05-05-2010-draft-preview_N.htm |work=[[USA Today]] |publisher= |date=May 11, 2009 |accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=\"PerloffSI\">{{citation |first=Andrew |last=Perloff |title=Sam Bradford goes No.1 to St. Louis Rams in 2010 NFL Mock Draft |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/andrew_perloff/04/28/2010/index.html |work=Sports Illustrated |date=April 28, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"CBS_2010_OT\">{{Citation |work=CBSSports.com |date= |title=NFL Draft \u2013 2010 OT Draft Prospects |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/prospectrankings/TSX/2010_OT }}</ref><ref name=\"Muench ESPN\">{{Citation |url=http://insider.espn.go.com/espn/blog/index?entryID=4744685&name=nfl_draft |last=Muench |first=Steve |date=December 15, 2009 |title=Okung leads trio of top-notch OTs |work=ESPN Insider }}</ref> and drew comparisons to [[D'Brickashaw Ferguson]].<ref name=\"CBS Okung Draft profile\">{{Citation |work=CBSSports.com |date= |title=Draft Profile: Russell Okung |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/players/1133637 }}</ref> According to [[NFL.com]]'s Gil Brandt, Okung \"will start and play a lot of years in the NFL.\"<ref name=\"BradtNFL\">{{Citation |last=Brandt |first=Gil |work=NFL.com |date= |title=Top offensive tackle prospects for 2010 hail from the Big 12 |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d811477a4 }}</ref> NFL.com's Bucky Brooks even projected Okung as the No. 1 pick overall,<ref name=\"BrooksNFL\">{{Citation |last=Brooks |first=Bucky |work=NFL.com |title=Never too soon to look at top prospects for next year's draft |url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/story?id=09000d5d81032985 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817013710/http://www.nfl.com/draft/story?id=09000d5d81032985 |archivedate=August 17, 2009 }}</ref> as did ''[[Scout.com]]\u2032s'' Chris Steuber.<ref name=\"Steuber Scout.com\">{{Citation |last=Steuber |first=Chris |date=May 1, 2009 |title=2010 Mock Draft |work=Scout.com |url=http://profootball.scout.com/a.z?s=127&p=2&c=861937 }}</ref> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''\u2032s Tony Pauline described Okung as \"a complete offensive tackle with a large upside\", who \"stands out in pass protection while also dominating as a run blocker\".<ref name=\"PaulineSImidseason\">{{Citation |last=Pauline |first=Tony |date=October 22, 2009 |title=2010 NFL Draft: Top 50 prospects |work=SI.com |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/football/nfl/10/21/draft.prospects/index.html }}</ref> The [[Kansas City Chiefs]] were believed to be one of the NFL teams to target Okung in the draft,<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.kansascity.com/669/story/1654293.html |title=Chiefs survey options as likely No. 3 pick in NFL Draft |first=Adam |last=Teicher |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |date=December 28, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100101130411/http://www.kansascity.com/669/story/1654293.html |archivedate=January 1, 2010 }}</ref> as well as the [[Washington Redskins]].<ref>{{Citation |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/02/25/AR2010022505463.html |title=Redskins will have plenty of offensive linemen from which to choose |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |date=February 26, 2010 |first=Rick |last=Maese |first2=Jason |last2=Reid }}.</ref>\n\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 5\u00bc\n|       weight = 307\n|         dash = 5.17\n|    ten split = 1.79\n| twenty split = 2.93\n|      shuttle = \n|   cone drill = \n|     vertical = \n|     broad ft = \n|     broad in = \n|        bench = 38\n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = 36\n|    hand span = 10\u00bd\n|         note = All values from NFL Combine.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/russell-okung?id=497032 |title=Russell Okung Combine Profile |work=NFL.com |accessdate=February 27, 2010 }}.</ref> No shuttles/jumps b/c of groin injury.\n}}\n\n===Seattle Seahawks===\nOkung was selected 6th overall by the [[Seattle Seahawks]], making him only the second Oklahoma State offensive lineman ever picked in the first round of an NFL Draft, along with [[John Ward (American football)|John Ward]], who was selected 25th overall by the [[Minnesota Vikings]] in [[1970 NFL Draft|1970]], and was the highest OSU draft pick since [[Barry Sanders]] went 3rd overall in the [[1989 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.nationalfootballpost.com/Wilson-Okung-is-impressive.html |title=Okung is impressive: Oklahoma State offensive tackle regarded as top 10 talent |first=Aaron |last=Wilson |work=National Football Post |date=February 26, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100302135731/http://www.nationalfootballpost.com/Wilson-Okung-is-impressive.html |archivedate=March 2, 2010 }}.</ref> On August 6, 2010, Okung was signed by the Seahawks to a six-year contract worth a maximum of $48 million, with more than $29 million in guaranteed money.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/trainingcamp10/news/story?id=5442653 |title=Russell Okung, Seattle Seahawks agree to six-year deal |publisher=ESPN |date=August 6, 2010 }}</ref> He was injured 6 games in his first NFL season high-ankle sprains on both ankles, but played well in the remaining 10. He saw limited action in the Seahawks' fourth game of the season in St. Louis against the Rams on October 3, before leaving the game in the first half after re-injuring his ankle.\n\nOkung started the first twelve games in the 2011 regular season for the Seahawks. On December 1, 2011, he suffered a season-ending injury late in Seattle's 31-14 victory over Philadelphia. [[Trent Cole]] flipped Okung over his back which resulted in Okung suffering a torn right pectoral muscle. He was put on Injury Reserve after the game.\n\nOkung started 15 games in the 2012 regular season for the Seahawks. He started both playoff games versus the Washington Redskins and Atlanta Falcons as well. 2012 marked Okung's first season without missing consecutive games since entering the NFL in 2010. He was voted as a starter in the 2012\u20132013 Pro Bowl making it his very first appearance. He was considered among many football analysts as being a top 5 Left Tackle in the 2012\u20132013 season while contributing to an offense that featured C [[Max Unger]], RB [[Marshawn Lynch]], and QB [[Russell Wilson]] in the Pro Bowl too.\n\nOkung started in only 8 games due to injury in 2013, but the Seahawks finished the season 13-3. In the playoffs, the Seahawks beat both the [[New Orleans Saints]] and [[San Francisco 49ers]] to reach [[Super Bowl XLVIII]]. The Seahawks won the Super Bowl 43-8 after they beat the [[Denver Broncos]] to give Okung his first [[Super Bowl ring]].\n\nOkung started 14 games in the 2014 season and help the Seahawks finish with a 12-4 record. The Seahawks beat both the [[Carolina Panthers]] and [[Green Bay Packers]] to reach [[Super Bowl XLIX]]. The Seahawks failed to repeat as Super Bowl champions after they lost 28\u201324 to the [[New England Patriots]].\n\nOkung started in 13 games in 2015 and the Seahawks finished with a 10-6 record and earned the #6 seed. The Seahawks defeated the [[Minnesota Vikings]] 10-9 in the Wild Card game, but lost 31-24 in the Divisional round to the Panthers.\n\n===Denver Broncos===\n[[File:Russel Okung Broncos Practice 2016 - 1.jpg|thumb|200px|Russell Okung Broncos \u2013 Practice 2016]]\nFollowing the end of his six-year contract with the [[Seattle Seahawks]] in 2016, Russell Okung opted to represent himself as a free agent in the NFL.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2015/07/21/russell-okung-thinks-more-nfl-players-should-represent-themselves/|title=Russell Okung thinks more NFL players should represent themselves|website=Washington Post|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000502703/article/russell-okung-to-test-free-agency-without-agent|title=Russell Okung to test free agency without agent|website=NFL.com|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Okung called his decision \"Betting on Myself.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theplayerstribune.com/russell-okung-seahawks-agents-in-sports/|title=Betting on Myself {{!}} By Russell Okung|website=The Players' Tribune|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> During his free agency, Okung met with the [[New York Giants]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/giants/index.ssf/2016/03/giants_to_host_free_agent_lt_russell_okung_per_rep.html|title=Giants to host free agent LT Russell Okung, per report|website=NJ.com|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/pittsburgh-steelers/post/_/id/18006/source-steelers-offer-contract-to-ot-russell-okung|title=Source: Steelers offer contract to OT Russell Okung|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> and [[Detroit Lions]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/story/sports/nfl/lions/2016/03/15/detroit-lions-russell-okung-decision/81830108/|title=Lions waiting on Russell Okung as OT market heats up|website=Detroit Free Press|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> was invited to visit with the San Francisco 49ers<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ninersnation.com/2016/3/10/11199414/49ers-have-reached-out-to-russell-okung-per-report|title=49ers have reached out to Russell Okung, per report|last=Fucillo|first=David|date=March 11, 2016|website=Niners Nation|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> and didn\u2019t initially rule-out resigning with the Seattle Seahawks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seahawks/okung-still-considering-seahawks-has-no-other-visits-planned-as-he-sifts-through-offers/|title=Russell Okung still considering Seahawks, has no other visits planned as he sifts through offers|date=March 14, 2016|website=The Seattle Times|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2016, Okung signed with the [[Denver Broncos]] on a one-year deal worth $5 million, which included an additional four-year, $48 million option.<ref>[http://www.denverbroncos.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/Broncos-sign-free-agent-OT-Russell-Okung-to-five-year-contract/1aa43137-fd5c-45c6-9e05-f7949085aaf2 Broncos sign free agent OT Russell Okung to five-year contract]</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Okung's Broncos deal contains no guaranteed money|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000645373/article/russell-okung-broncos-agree-to-a-fiveyear-deal?campaign=tw-nf-sf22741565-sf22741565|website=NFL.com|accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref> The contract he negotiated for himself for 2016, had no guaranteed money and was extremely team-friendly and incentive-laden and is solely based on his performance. Had the Broncos exercised the option to retain him in 2017 he would have received $21 million guaranteed for 2017 and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.spotrac.com/nfl/denver-broncos/russell-okung-6515/|title=Sportac.com: Russell Okung contracts|access-date=November 6, 2016|website=Spotrac.com}}</ref> He ended up starting all 16 games at left tackle for the Broncos in 2016.\n\nOn February 23, 2017, the Broncos declined Okung's option on his contract, making him a free agent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Denver Broncos don't pick up Russell Okung's option|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000787464/article/denver-broncos-dont-pick-up-russell-okungs-option|author=Orr, Conor|website=NFL.com|date=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Los Angeles Chargers ===\nOn March 9, 2017, Okung signed a four-year, $53 million contract with the [[Los Angeles Chargers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000792017/article/chargers-beat-out-vikings-to-land-russell-okung |title=Chargers beat out Vikings to land Russell Okung |last=Wesseling |first=Chris |date=March 9, 2017 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> He started 15 games at left tackle in his first year as a Charger, on his way to his second Pro Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chargers.com/news/2018/01/22/russell-okung-named-2018-pro-bowl |title=Russell Okung Named to 2018 Pro Bowl |last=Elwood |first=Hayley |date=January 22, 2018 |website=Chargers.com}}</ref> He followed that up in 2018 with 15 starts at left tackle, missing one game with a groin injury.\n\nDuring the 2019 offseason, Okung suffered a pulmonary embolism due to blood clots in his lungs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chargers\u2019 Russell Okung survived \u2018near-death\u2019 experience after blood clot in lung|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/chargers/story/2019-07-25/russell-okung-near-death-experience-chargers-training-camp|work=Los Angeles Times|date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> He was placed on the reserve/non-football illness list to start the season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chargers Announce Roster Moves|url=https://www.chargers.com/news/chargers-announce-roster-moves-x6572|website=Chargers.com|date=August 31, 2019}}</ref> He was activated off NFI on October 26, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chargers place FS Nasir Adderley on IR, activate OT Russell Okung|url=https://chargerswire.usatoday.com/2019/10/26/chargers-place-fs-nasir-adderley-on-ir-activate-ot-russell-okung/|work=Chargers Wire|publisher=USA Today|date=October 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Carolina Panthers===\nOn March 4, 2020, the Chargers agreed to trade Okung to the [[Carolina Panthers]] in exchange for guard [[Trai Turner]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Chargers, Panthers set to swap Okung for Turner|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001105240/article/chargers-panthers-set-to-swap-okung-for-turner|author=Shook, Nick|website=NFL.com|date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> The deal became official on March 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.panthers.com/news/panthers-officially-acquire-russell-okung|title= Panthers officially acquire LT Russell Okung|work=Panthers.com|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020|first=Will|last=Bryan}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRussell Okung is the son of  Akpabio and Victor Okung. Okung, who graduated in 2009, was a marketing major at OSU.<ref>{{Citation |last=Nulph |first=Scott |date=August 8, 2009 |title=After passing up NFL, OSU's Okung eager for final year |newspaper=Stillwater NewsPress |url=http://www.stillwater-newspress.com/osusports/local_story_220212735.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090905134841/http://www.stillwater-newspress.com/osusports/local_story_220212735.html |archivedate=September 5, 2009 }}</ref> He is of [[Nigeria]]n ancestry.<ref>[http://www.overtimeafrica.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=259:nfl-draft-player-profiles&catid=36:featured 2010 NFL Draft: Player Profiles] Overtime Africa, April 13, 2010</ref>\n\nOkung is a [[Christianity|Christian]]. Okung has spoken about his faith saying, \"[[Jesus]] is everything. And the great thing about Jesus is He'll meet you right where you're at. It's free. You don't have to earn it. You don't have to work for it. He gives it because He loves us and He is full of grace.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/seattle-seahawks-russell-wilson-players-agree-with-assistant-coach-jesus-is-better-than-super-bowl-112892/|title=Seattle Seahawks' Russell Wilson, Players Agree With Assistant Coach: 'Jesus Is Better Than Super Bowl'}}</ref> Okung's favorite [[Bible]] verse is [[Epistle to the Romans|Romans]] 4:20.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fca.org/2014/01/17/6-questions-with-russell-okung/#.Uto6-hXnbIU|title=6 Questions With Russell Okung}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, 2016, Okung responded to Paul Graham's essay on economic equality and startups in an essay published on GeekWire: \"[[Economic inequality]] isn\u2019t the symptom; it's the virus that attacks. You, Graham, like the rest of America, have been deceived. You are a victim of the American Dream, the belief that anyone who works hard can move up economically regardless of his or her social circumstances. American cultural optimism is one of the greatest lies ever told.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Seahawks lineman Russell Okung responds to Paul Graham's essay on economic inequality and startups|url=http://www.geekwire.com/2016/seahawks-lineman-russell-okung-responds-paul-grahams-essay-inequality-startups/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Okung co-founded the Greater Foundation, an organization that \"aims to equip the next generation with the tools to reach their highest potential through mentoring and leadership development.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seahawks.com/news/2016/02/26/seahawks-left-tackle-russell-okung-launches-greater-foundation|title=Seahawks Left Tackle Russell Okung Launches Greater Foundation|date=February 26, 2016|website=Seattle Seahawks|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.begreater.org/about/|title=About|website=The Greater Foundation|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Through the Foundation and through other personal effort, Okung focuses on providing access and opportunity for underserved youth, particularly in the tech sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geekwire.com/2016/seahawks-lineman-russell-okung-looks-to-expose-at-risk-teens-to-technology-with-new-startup-greater/|title=Seahawks lineman Russell Okung exposes at-risk teens to technology with new non-profit GREATER|date=January 29, 2016|website=GeekWire|language=en-US|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Okung is also interested in the startup world and entrepreneurship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mynorthwest.com/215534/seahawks-russell-okung-demolishing-stereotypes-as-entrepreneur/|title=Seahawks' Russell Okung demolishing stereotypes as entrepreneur|date=February 25, 2016|website=MyNorthwest.com|language=en-US|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ceoblognation.com/2016/02/three-startup-lessons-from-seattle-seahawks-left-tackle-russell-okung-seahawks/|title=Three Startup Lessons From Seattle Seahawks Left Tackle Russell Okung [Seahawks] \u2013 Business Startup ideas, Entrepreneur News, Tips {{!}} CEO Blog Nation|date=February 12, 2016|website=Business Startup ideas, Entrepreneur News, Tips {{!}} CEO Blog Nation|language=en-US|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Most recently in 2019, he has been open about his support for Bitcoin. He and fellow NFL player Matt Barkley have recently requested their salaries be paid in Bitcoin but both requests were denied.<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=RussellOkung |number=1128432919628804099 |date = 14 May 2019 |title=How I feel after being introduced to #BitcoinTwitter...}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet |user=RussellOkung |number=1128340077841543168 |date = 14 May 2019 |title=I\u2019m part of the revolution. Long $BTC, short the bankers.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet |user=RussellOkung |number=1135943842752942080 |date = 4 Jun 2019 |title=Consider this tweet your next touchpoint. #BuyBitcoin}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/nfl-pro-bowler-russell-okung-183025598.html|title=NFL Pro Bowler Russell Okung Plugs Bitcoin in Locker Room|date=May 30, 2019|website=Yahoo Finance|}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2836553-49ers-bengals-rejected-matt-barkleys-request-to-pay-his-contracts-in-bitcoin|title=49ers, Bengals Rejected Matt Barkley's Request to Pay His Contracts in Bitcoin|date=May 16, 2019|website=Bleacherreport.com|}}</ref> Okung has also launched his own Bitcoin brand and event series, \"Bitcoin Is _\", which had its inaugural installment on September 1, 2019 in Los Angeles.<ref>https://www.bitcoinis.com/</ref>\n\nIn April of 2020, Okung launched Okung Ventures <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://okungventures.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.chargers.com/team/players/roster/russell-okung Los Angeles Chargers bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160304173255/http://www.seahawks.com/team/players/roster/russell-okung Seattle Seahawks bio] \n*[http://www.denverbroncos.com/team/roster/Russell-Okung/26511820-959a-45cc-b433-eeef9f8c0e2e Denver Broncos bio]\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150612094422/http://www.okstate.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/okung_russell00.html Oklahoma State Cowboys bio]\n\n{{2009 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{2010 NFL Draft}}\n{{SeahawksFirstPick}}\n{{Seahawks2010DraftPicks}}\n{{Super Bowl XLVIII}}\n{{Carolina Panthers roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Okung, Russell}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American Christians]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American football offensive tackles]]\n[[Category:American people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:Carolina Panthers players]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Chargers players]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Nigerian players of American football]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma State Cowboys football players]]\n[[Category:People from Richmond, Texas]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:Seattle Seahawks players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Houston metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football offensive tackle}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Russell Okung\n|image= Russell Okung 2016.jpg\n|image_size=\n|alt=\n|caption= Okung with the Denver Broncos in 2016\n|current_team =Carolina Panthers\n|number=\n|position=[[Offensive tackle]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1988|10|7|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Houston, Texas]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 5\n|weight_lbs = 310\n|high_school = [[George Bush High School|George Bush]]<br>([[Richmond, Texas]])\n|college=[[Oklahoma State Cowboys football|Oklahoma State]]\n|draftyear=2010\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=6\n|pastteams=\n* [[Seattle Seahawks]] ({{NFL Year|2010}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2015}})\n* [[Denver Broncos]] ({{NFL Year|2016}})\n* [[Los Angeles Chargers]] ({{NFL Year|2017}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2019}})\n* [[Carolina Panthers]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n|status=Active\n|highlights=\n* [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XLVIII|XLVIII]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2013 Pro Bowl|2012]], [[2018 Pro Bowl|2017]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[All-American]] ([[2008 College Football All-America Team|2008]], [[2009 College Football All-America Team|2009]])\n* [[Touchdown Club of Columbus#The Jim Parker Trophy|Jim Parker Trophy]] (2009)\n* [[Big 12 Offensive Lineman of the Year]] (2009)\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-Big 12 (2008, 2009)\n* Dick Bogert Award (2006)\n|statweek=\n|statseason=2019\n|statlabel1=Games played\n|statvalue1=124\n|statlabel2=Games started\n|statvalue2=124\n|nflnew=russellokung/497032\n}}\n\n'''Russell Okung''' ({{IPAc-en|o\u028a|\u02c8|k|\u028a|\u014b}} {{respell|oh|KUUNG|'}}; born October 7, 1988<ref>[http://www.russellokung.com/about/ About Russell Okung]</ref>) is an [[American football]] [[offensive tackle]] for the [[Carolina Panthers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] for [[Oklahoma State University]], and was twice recognized as an [[All-American]]. He was drafted by the [[Seattle Seahawks]] with the sixth overall pick in the [[2010 NFL Draft]], and has also played for the [[Denver Broncos]] and the [[Los Angeles Chargers]].\n\n==Early years==\nOkung was born in [[Houston, Texas]].  He attended [[George Bush High School]] in Fort Bend, where he was a first-team All-Greater Houston and first-team all-district selection.  He was also one of the state's top performers in the [[discus throw]] (PR of 47.50 meters). Considered a three-star prospect by ''[[Rivals.com]]'',<ref>{{citation |title=Russell Okung Profile |url=https://footballrecruiting.rivals.com/viewprospect.asp?pr_key=40016&sport=1 |work=Rivals.com |accessdate= }}</ref> Okung was listed as the No. 33 offensive tackle prospect in the class of 2006.<ref>{{Citation |url=https://footballrecruiting.rivals.com/viewrank.asp?ra_key=1150 |title=Offensive tackles 2006 |work=Rivals.com |date=January 30, 2006 }}.</ref>  At {{convert|250|lb|kg|0}} coming out of high school, he did not possess the prototypical tackle bulk.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://insider.espn.go.com/ncf/recruiting/tracker/player?recruitId=35168 |work=ESPN |title=Russell Okung Recruiting Profile |date=February 1, 2006 }}.</ref>  Okung was recruited by a number of major schools, including [[University of Oklahoma|Oklahoma]], [[Louisiana State University|LSU]], and [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln|Nebraska]]. He committed to Oklahoma State in January 2006.\n\n==College career==\nOkung attended [[Oklahoma State University]], where he played for coach [[Mike Gundy]]'s [[Oklahoma State Cowboys football]] team from 2006 to 2009.  As a [[true freshman]], he moved into the starting lineup for the first time against [[University of Kansas|Kansas]] and held the position of right tackle for the rest of the season (eight straight starts). He ended the season by being voted as a member of All-Big 12 freshman team (by ''[[The Sporting News]]'') and was named the Dick Bogert Award winner as Oklahoma State's top freshman.\n\nIn his sophomore season, he started all thirteen games, having been moved permanently to left tackle. The Cowboys\u2019 offensive line gave up just five sacks in eight Big 12 games to lead the league in that category. Okung earned honorable mention all-Big 12 honors (by coaches). He was also named to the ''Rivals.com'' all-bowl team after holding Indiana's [[Greg Middleton]], the NCAA's sack leader, without a tackle in the [[2007 Insight Bowl]] victory.<ref>{{Citation |work=Rivals.com |date=January 9, 2008 |title=Coming up big in the biggest games |url=http://collegefootball.rivals.com/content.asp?SID=1144&CID=759478 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080520153800/http://collegefootball.rivals.com/content.asp?SID=1144&CID=759478 |archivedate=May 20, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Russel Okung Broncos Practice 2016 - 2.jpg|thumb|left]]\nAs a junior, Okung led Oklahoma State with 71 knockdown blocks, and was named a first-team all-conference selection by the coaches.  He also was named to ''[[Pro Football Weekly]]''\u2032s 2008 All-America team.<ref>{{Citation |first=Nolan |last=Nawrocki |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Pro Football Weekly's 2008 All-America team |url=http://www.profootballweekly.com/PFW/College+Football/College+Football+Extras/2008/allamerica.htm |work=Pro Football Weekly |publisher= |date=December 22, 2008 |accessdate= }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  Okung currently has started 34 straight games for the longest active streak on the team.\n\nIn 2009, Okung was listed at No. 1 on ''[[Rivals.com]]\u2032s'' preseason offensive tackle power ranking.<ref>{{Citation |last=Buchanan |first=Olin |last2=Dienhart |first2=Tom |last3=Fox |first3=David |last4=Huguenin |first4=Mike |last5=Megargee |first5=Steve |date=August 22, 2009 |title=Preseason offensive tackle power rankings |work=Rivals.com |url=http://rivals100.rivals.com/content.asp?cid=978914 }}</ref> He was also named to the 2009 [[Outland Trophy]] watch list.<ref name=\"FWAA Outland\">{{Citation |last=Richardson |first=Steve |date=August 11, 2009 |title=2009 Outland Trophy Watch List Announced |publisher=[[Football Writers Association of America]] |url=http://www.sportswriters.net/fwaa/news/2009/outland090811.html }}</ref> On October 14, 2009, Okung was named one of twelve semifinalists\u2014and the only offensive lineman\u2014for the [[Lombardi Award]].<ref>{{Citation |date=October 14, 2009 |title=Okung Named Lombardi Semi-Finalist |work=OK State Athletics |url=http://www.okstate.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/101409aaa.html }}</ref>\n\nIn a game against [[2009 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]] on October 10, Okung held then-NCAA sack leader, [[Von Miller]], without a quarterback sack. That effort was the second time during his career he has not allowed a sack against the nation's leader at the time. Against [[2009 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]] on October 31, Okung held the Longhorn pass rush, including All-American candidate [[Sergio Kindle]], without a quarterback sack. According to ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'s'' Tony Pauline, that performance \"has solidified his projection as the top senior tackle\" in the 2010 NFL Draft.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/football/nfl/11/02/risers/ |title=Sam Bradford, 2010 NFL Draft, rising, sliding prospects |work=Sports Illustrated |last=Pauline |first=Tony |date=November 2, 2009 }}</ref> On November 24, 2009, Okung was named one of three finalists for the 2009 [[Outland Trophy]], alongside [[Mike Iupati]] and [[Ndamukong Suh]].<ref name=\"GriffinESPNOutland\">{{Citation |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/ncfnation/post/_/id/14004/okung-suh-named-outland-trophy-finalists |title=Okung, Suh named Outland Trophy finalists |last=Griffin |first=Tom |work=ESPN |date=November 24, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOn December 1, 2009, Okung was named Big 12 Offensive Lineman of the Year in a vote of the league's coaches.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.okstate.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/120109aaa.html |title=Okung Named Big 12 O-Lineman of the Year |work=Oklahoma State Athletics |date=December 1, 2009 }}</ref>  He was also recognized as a unanimous first-team [[2009 College Football All-America Team|2009 All-American]].<ref>{{Citation |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/big12/post/_/id/8482/seven-big-12-players-make-consensus-all-america-list |title=Seven Big 12 players make All-America list |last=Griffin |first=Tim |publisher=ESPN |date=December 17, 2009 }}</ref> Despite tweaking his knee in practice earlier that week, Okung played in the [[2010 Cotton Bowl Classic]] to end his career at Oklahoma State with a streak of 47 straight starts.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.newsok.com/osus-russell-okung-likely-to-play-in-cotton-bowl/article/3428640 |newspaper=The Oklahoman |title=OSU's Russell Okung likely to play in Cotton Bowl |date=December 31, 2009 |last=Chatmon |first=Brandon |last2=Helsley |first2=John }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=300020145 |title=McCluster's 182 yards, two TDs propel Ole Miss to Cotton Bowl victory |work=ESPN |date=January 2, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n[[File:Russell Okung.jpg|thumb|150px|Okung with the Seattle Seahawks in 2013]]\n\nOkung was considered one of the best offensive tackles available in the [[2010 NFL Draft]],<ref name=\"PriscoCBS\">{{Citation |first=Pete |last=Prisco |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Prisco's 2010 draft preview: QB will land No. 1 spot |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/story/11684517 |work=CBSSports.com |publisher= |date=April 27, 2009 |accessdate= }}</ref><ref name=\"CooneyUSAToday\">{{Citation |first=Frank |last=Cooney |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Who's next? Looking ahead to the best of the 2010 draft class |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/2009-05-05-2010-draft-preview_N.htm |work=[[USA Today]] |publisher= |date=May 11, 2009 |accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=\"PerloffSI\">{{citation |first=Andrew |last=Perloff |title=Sam Bradford goes No.1 to St. Louis Rams in 2010 NFL Mock Draft |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/andrew_perloff/04/28/2010/index.html |work=Sports Illustrated |date=April 28, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"CBS_2010_OT\">{{Citation |work=CBSSports.com |date= |title=NFL Draft \u2013 2010 OT Draft Prospects |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/prospectrankings/TSX/2010_OT }}</ref><ref name=\"Muench ESPN\">{{Citation |url=http://insider.espn.go.com/espn/blog/index?entryID=4744685&name=nfl_draft |last=Muench |first=Steve |date=December 15, 2009 |title=Okung leads trio of top-notch OTs |work=ESPN Insider }}</ref> and drew comparisons to [[D'Brickashaw Ferguson]].<ref name=\"CBS Okung Draft profile\">{{Citation |work=CBSSports.com |date= |title=Draft Profile: Russell Okung |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/players/1133637 }}</ref> According to [[NFL.com]]'s Gil Brandt, Okung \"will start and play a lot of years in the NFL.\"<ref name=\"BradtNFL\">{{Citation |last=Brandt |first=Gil |work=NFL.com |date= |title=Top offensive tackle prospects for 2010 hail from the Big 12 |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d811477a4 }}</ref> NFL.com's Bucky Brooks even projected Okung as the No. 1 pick overall,<ref name=\"BrooksNFL\">{{Citation |last=Brooks |first=Bucky |work=NFL.com |title=Never too soon to look at top prospects for next year's draft |url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/story?id=09000d5d81032985 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817013710/http://www.nfl.com/draft/story?id=09000d5d81032985 |archivedate=August 17, 2009 }}</ref> as did ''[[Scout.com]]\u2032s'' Chris Steuber.<ref name=\"Steuber Scout.com\">{{Citation |last=Steuber |first=Chris |date=May 1, 2009 |title=2010 Mock Draft |work=Scout.com |url=http://profootball.scout.com/a.z?s=127&p=2&c=861937 }}</ref> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''\u2032s Tony Pauline described Okung as \"a complete offensive tackle with a large upside\", who \"stands out in pass protection while also dominating as a run blocker\".<ref name=\"PaulineSImidseason\">{{Citation |last=Pauline |first=Tony |date=October 22, 2009 |title=2010 NFL Draft: Top 50 prospects |work=SI.com |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/football/nfl/10/21/draft.prospects/index.html }}</ref> The [[Kansas City Chiefs]] were believed to be one of the NFL teams to target Okung in the draft,<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.kansascity.com/669/story/1654293.html |title=Chiefs survey options as likely No. 3 pick in NFL Draft |first=Adam |last=Teicher |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |date=December 28, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100101130411/http://www.kansascity.com/669/story/1654293.html |archivedate=January 1, 2010 }}</ref> as well as the [[Washington Redskins]].<ref>{{Citation |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/02/25/AR2010022505463.html |title=Redskins will have plenty of offensive linemen from which to choose |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |date=February 26, 2010 |first=Rick |last=Maese |first2=Jason |last2=Reid }}.</ref>\n\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 5\u00bc\n|       weight = 307\n|         dash = 5.17\n|    ten split = 1.79\n| twenty split = 2.93\n|      shuttle = \n|   cone drill = \n|     vertical = \n|     broad ft = \n|     broad in = \n|        bench = 38\n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = 36\n|    hand span = 10\u00bd\n|         note = All values from NFL Combine.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/russell-okung?id=497032 |title=Russell Okung Combine Profile |work=NFL.com |accessdate=February 27, 2010 }}.</ref> No shuttles/jumps b/c of groin injury.\n}}\n\n===Seattle Seahawks===\nOkung was selected 6th overall by the [[Seattle Seahawks]], making him only the second Oklahoma State offensive lineman ever picked in the first round of an NFL Draft, along with [[John Ward (American football)|John Ward]], who was selected 25th overall by the [[Minnesota Vikings]] in [[1970 NFL Draft|1970]], and was the highest OSU draft pick since [[Barry Sanders]] went 3rd overall in the [[1989 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.nationalfootballpost.com/Wilson-Okung-is-impressive.html |title=Okung is impressive: Oklahoma State offensive tackle regarded as top 10 talent |first=Aaron |last=Wilson |work=National Football Post |date=February 26, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100302135731/http://www.nationalfootballpost.com/Wilson-Okung-is-impressive.html |archivedate=March 2, 2010 }}.</ref> On August 6, 2010, Okung was signed by the Seahawks to a six-year contract worth a maximum of $48 million, with more than $29 million in guaranteed money.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/trainingcamp10/news/story?id=5442653 |title=Russell Okung, Seattle Seahawks agree to six-year deal |publisher=ESPN |date=August 6, 2010 }}</ref> He was injured 6 games in his first NFL season high-ankle sprains on both ankles, but played well in the remaining 10. He saw limited action in the Seahawks' fourth game of the season in St. Louis against the Rams on October 3, before leaving the game in the first half after re-injuring his ankle.\n\nOkung started the first twelve games in the 2011 regular season for the Seahawks. On December 1, 2011, he suffered a season-ending injury late in Seattle's 31-14 victory over Philadelphia. [[Trent Cole]] flipped Okung over his back which resulted in Okung suffering a torn right pectoral muscle. He was put on Injury Reserve after the game.\n\nOkung started 15 games in the 2012 regular season for the Seahawks. He started both playoff games versus the Washington Redskins and Atlanta Falcons as well. 2012 marked Okung's first season without missing consecutive games since entering the NFL in 2010. He was voted as a starter in the 2012\u20132013 Pro Bowl making it his very first appearance. He was considered among many football analysts as being a top 5 Left Tackle in the 2012\u20132013 season while contributing to an offense that featured C [[Max Unger]], RB [[Marshawn Lynch]], and QB [[Russell Wilson]] in the Pro Bowl too.\n\nOkung started in only 8 games due to injury in 2013, but the Seahawks finished the season 13-3. In the playoffs, the Seahawks beat both the [[New Orleans Saints]] and [[San Francisco 49ers]] to reach [[Super Bowl XLVIII]]. The Seahawks won the Super Bowl 43-8 after they beat the [[Denver Broncos]] to give Okung his first [[Super Bowl ring]].\n\nOkung started 14 games in the 2014 season and help the Seahawks finish with a 12-4 record. The Seahawks beat both the [[Carolina Panthers]] and [[Green Bay Packers]] to reach [[Super Bowl XLIX]]. The Seahawks failed to repeat as Super Bowl champions after they lost 28\u201324 to the [[New England Patriots]].\n\nOkung started in 13 games in 2015 and the Seahawks finished with a 10-6 record and earned the #6 seed. The Seahawks defeated the [[Minnesota Vikings]] 10-9 in the Wild Card game, but lost 31-24 in the Divisional round to the Panthers.\n\n===Denver Broncos===\n[[File:Russel Okung Broncos Practice 2016 - 1.jpg|thumb|200px|Russell Okung Broncos \u2013 Practice 2016]]\nFollowing the end of his six-year contract with the [[Seattle Seahawks]] in 2016, Russell Okung opted to represent himself as a free agent in the NFL.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2015/07/21/russell-okung-thinks-more-nfl-players-should-represent-themselves/|title=Russell Okung thinks more NFL players should represent themselves|website=Washington Post|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000502703/article/russell-okung-to-test-free-agency-without-agent|title=Russell Okung to test free agency without agent|website=NFL.com|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Okung called his decision \"Betting on Myself.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theplayerstribune.com/russell-okung-seahawks-agents-in-sports/|title=Betting on Myself {{!}} By Russell Okung|website=The Players' Tribune|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> During his free agency, Okung met with the [[New York Giants]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/giants/index.ssf/2016/03/giants_to_host_free_agent_lt_russell_okung_per_rep.html|title=Giants to host free agent LT Russell Okung, per report|website=NJ.com|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/pittsburgh-steelers/post/_/id/18006/source-steelers-offer-contract-to-ot-russell-okung|title=Source: Steelers offer contract to OT Russell Okung|website=ESPN.com|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> and [[Detroit Lions]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/story/sports/nfl/lions/2016/03/15/detroit-lions-russell-okung-decision/81830108/|title=Lions waiting on Russell Okung as OT market heats up|website=Detroit Free Press|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> was invited to visit with the San Francisco 49ers<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ninersnation.com/2016/3/10/11199414/49ers-have-reached-out-to-russell-okung-per-report|title=49ers have reached out to Russell Okung, per report|last=Fucillo|first=David|date=March 11, 2016|website=Niners Nation|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> and didn\u2019t initially rule-out resigning with the Seattle Seahawks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seahawks/okung-still-considering-seahawks-has-no-other-visits-planned-as-he-sifts-through-offers/|title=Russell Okung still considering Seahawks, has no other visits planned as he sifts through offers|date=March 14, 2016|website=The Seattle Times|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2016, Okung signed with the [[Denver Broncos]] on a one-year deal worth $5 million, which included an additional four-year, $48 million option.<ref>[http://www.denverbroncos.com/news-and-blogs/article-1/Broncos-sign-free-agent-OT-Russell-Okung-to-five-year-contract/1aa43137-fd5c-45c6-9e05-f7949085aaf2 Broncos sign free agent OT Russell Okung to five-year contract]</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Okung's Broncos deal contains no guaranteed money|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000645373/article/russell-okung-broncos-agree-to-a-fiveyear-deal?campaign=tw-nf-sf22741565-sf22741565|website=NFL.com|accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref> The contract he negotiated for himself for 2016, had no guaranteed money and was extremely team-friendly and incentive-laden and is solely based on his performance. Had the Broncos exercised the option to retain him in 2017 he would have received $21 million guaranteed for 2017 and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.spotrac.com/nfl/denver-broncos/russell-okung-6515/|title=Sportac.com: Russell Okung contracts|access-date=November 6, 2016|website=Spotrac.com}}</ref> He ended up starting all 16 games at left tackle for the Broncos in 2016.\n\nOn February 23, 2017, the Broncos declined Okung's option on his contract, making him a free agent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Denver Broncos don't pick up Russell Okung's option|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000787464/article/denver-broncos-dont-pick-up-russell-okungs-option|author=Orr, Conor|website=NFL.com|date=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Los Angeles Chargers ===\nOn March 9, 2017, Okung signed a four-year, $53 million contract with the [[Los Angeles Chargers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000792017/article/chargers-beat-out-vikings-to-land-russell-okung |title=Chargers beat out Vikings to land Russell Okung |last=Wesseling |first=Chris |date=March 9, 2017 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> He started 15 games at left tackle in his first year as a Charger, on his way to his second Pro Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chargers.com/news/2018/01/22/russell-okung-named-2018-pro-bowl |title=Russell Okung Named to 2018 Pro Bowl |last=Elwood |first=Hayley |date=January 22, 2018 |website=Chargers.com}}</ref> He followed that up in 2018 with 15 starts at left tackle, missing one game with a groin injury.\n\nDuring the 2019 offseason, Okung suffered a pulmonary embolism due to blood clots in his lungs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chargers\u2019 Russell Okung survived \u2018near-death\u2019 experience after blood clot in lung|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/chargers/story/2019-07-25/russell-okung-near-death-experience-chargers-training-camp|work=Los Angeles Times|date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> He was placed on the reserve/non-football illness list to start the season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chargers Announce Roster Moves|url=https://www.chargers.com/news/chargers-announce-roster-moves-x6572|website=Chargers.com|date=August 31, 2019}}</ref> He was activated off NFI on October 26, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chargers place FS Nasir Adderley on IR, activate OT Russell Okung|url=https://chargerswire.usatoday.com/2019/10/26/chargers-place-fs-nasir-adderley-on-ir-activate-ot-russell-okung/|work=Chargers Wire|publisher=USA Today|date=October 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Carolina Panthers===\nOn March 4, 2020, the Chargers agreed to trade Okung to the [[Carolina Panthers]] in exchange for guard [[Trai Turner]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Chargers, Panthers set to swap Okung for Turner|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001105240/article/chargers-panthers-set-to-swap-okung-for-turner|author=Shook, Nick|website=NFL.com|date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> The deal became official on March 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.panthers.com/news/panthers-officially-acquire-russell-okung|title= Panthers officially acquire LT Russell Okung|work=Panthers.com|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020|first=Will|last=Bryan}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRussell Okung is the son of  Akpabio and Victor Okung. Okung, who graduated in 2009, was a marketing major at OSU.<ref>{{Citation |last=Nulph |first=Scott |date=August 8, 2009 |title=After passing up NFL, OSU's Okung eager for final year |newspaper=Stillwater NewsPress |url=http://www.stillwater-newspress.com/osusports/local_story_220212735.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090905134841/http://www.stillwater-newspress.com/osusports/local_story_220212735.html |archivedate=September 5, 2009 }}</ref> He is of [[Nigeria]]n ancestry.<ref>[http://www.overtimeafrica.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=259:nfl-draft-player-profiles&catid=36:featured 2010 NFL Draft: Player Profiles] Overtime Africa, April 13, 2010</ref>\n\nOkung is a [[Christianity|Christian]]. Okung has spoken about his faith saying, \"[[Jesus]] is everything. And the great thing about Jesus is He'll meet you right where you're at. It's free. You don't have to earn it. You don't have to work for it. He gives it because He loves us and He is full of grace.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/seattle-seahawks-russell-wilson-players-agree-with-assistant-coach-jesus-is-better-than-super-bowl-112892/|title=Seattle Seahawks' Russell Wilson, Players Agree With Assistant Coach: 'Jesus Is Better Than Super Bowl'}}</ref> Okung's favorite [[Bible]] verse is [[Epistle to the Romans|Romans]] 4:20.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fca.org/2014/01/17/6-questions-with-russell-okung/#.Uto6-hXnbIU|title=6 Questions With Russell Okung}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, 2016, Okung responded to Paul Graham's essay on economic equality and startups in an essay published on GeekWire: \"[[Economic inequality]] isn\u2019t the symptom; it's the virus that attacks. You, Graham, like the rest of America, have been deceived. You are a victim of the American Dream, the belief that anyone who works hard can move up economically regardless of his or her social circumstances. American cultural optimism is one of the greatest lies ever told.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Seahawks lineman Russell Okung responds to Paul Graham's essay on economic inequality and startups|url=http://www.geekwire.com/2016/seahawks-lineman-russell-okung-responds-paul-grahams-essay-inequality-startups/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Okung co-founded the Greater Foundation, an organization that \"aims to equip the next generation with the tools to reach their highest potential through mentoring and leadership development.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seahawks.com/news/2016/02/26/seahawks-left-tackle-russell-okung-launches-greater-foundation|title=Seahawks Left Tackle Russell Okung Launches Greater Foundation|date=February 26, 2016|website=Seattle Seahawks|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.begreater.org/about/|title=About|website=The Greater Foundation|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Through the Foundation and through other personal effort, Okung focuses on providing access and opportunity for underserved youth, particularly in the tech sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geekwire.com/2016/seahawks-lineman-russell-okung-looks-to-expose-at-risk-teens-to-technology-with-new-startup-greater/|title=Seahawks lineman Russell Okung exposes at-risk teens to technology with new non-profit GREATER|date=January 29, 2016|website=GeekWire|language=en-US|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Okung is also interested in the startup world and entrepreneurship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mynorthwest.com/215534/seahawks-russell-okung-demolishing-stereotypes-as-entrepreneur/|title=Seahawks' Russell Okung demolishing stereotypes as entrepreneur|date=February 25, 2016|website=MyNorthwest.com|language=en-US|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ceoblognation.com/2016/02/three-startup-lessons-from-seattle-seahawks-left-tackle-russell-okung-seahawks/|title=Three Startup Lessons From Seattle Seahawks Left Tackle Russell Okung [Seahawks] \u2013 Business Startup ideas, Entrepreneur News, Tips {{!}} CEO Blog Nation|date=February 12, 2016|website=Business Startup ideas, Entrepreneur News, Tips {{!}} CEO Blog Nation|language=en-US|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Most recently in 2019, he has been open about his support for Bitcoin. He and fellow NFL player Matt Barkley have recently requested their salaries be paid in Bitcoin but both requests were denied.<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=RussellOkung |number=1128432919628804099 |date = 14 May 2019 |title=How I feel after being introduced to #BitcoinTwitter...}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet |user=RussellOkung |number=1128340077841543168 |date = 14 May 2019 |title=I\u2019m part of the revolution. Long $BTC, short the bankers.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet |user=RussellOkung |number=1135943842752942080 |date = 4 Jun 2019 |title=Consider this tweet your next touchpoint. #BuyBitcoin}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/nfl-pro-bowler-russell-okung-183025598.html|title=NFL Pro Bowler Russell Okung Plugs Bitcoin in Locker Room|date=May 30, 2019|website=Yahoo Finance|}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2836553-49ers-bengals-rejected-matt-barkleys-request-to-pay-his-contracts-in-bitcoin|title=49ers, Bengals Rejected Matt Barkley's Request to Pay His Contracts in Bitcoin|date=May 16, 2019|website=Bleacherreport.com|}}</ref> Okung has also launched his own Bitcoin brand and event series, \"Bitcoin Is _\", which had its inaugural installment on September 1, 2019 in Los Angeles.<ref>https://www.bitcoinis.com/</ref>\n\nIn April of 2020, Okung launched Okung Ventures <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://okungventures.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.chargers.com/team/players/roster/russell-okung Los Angeles Chargers bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160304173255/http://www.seahawks.com/team/players/roster/russell-okung Seattle Seahawks bio] \n*[http://www.denverbroncos.com/team/roster/Russell-Okung/26511820-959a-45cc-b433-eeef9f8c0e2e Denver Broncos bio]\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150612094422/http://www.okstate.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/okung_russell00.html Oklahoma State Cowboys bio]\n\n{{2009 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{2010 NFL Draft}}\n{{SeahawksFirstPick}}\n{{Seahawks2010DraftPicks}}\n{{Super Bowl XLVIII}}\n{{Carolina Panthers roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Okung, Russell}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American Christians]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American football offensive tackles]]\n[[Category:American people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:Carolina Panthers players]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Chargers players]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Nigerian players of American football]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma State Cowboys football players]]\n[[Category:People from Richmond, Texas]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:Seattle Seahawks players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Houston metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n", "name_user": "Playzman123", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_Okung"}
{"title_page": "Ludger Sylbaris", "text_new": "[[File:Cyparis.jpg|thumb|270px|right|A postcard featuring Sylbaris/Cyparis labelled \"survivor of Saint-Pierre\".]]\n\n'''Ludger \"Samson\" Sylbaris''' (1 June 1874<ref>[[Peter Morgan|Morgan, Peter]]. Fire Mountain, {{ISBN | 1-58234-199-0}}, Bloomsbury. New York, NY: 2003. 42-43.</ref> &ndash; {{c.}} 1929) was an [[Afro-Caribbean]] man who was one of two survivors in the city of [[Saint-Pierre, Martinique|Saint-Pierre]] on the Caribbean island of [[Martinique]] during the [[Mount Pel\u00e9e#1902 eruption|devastating volcanic eruption of Mount Pelee]] on May 8, 1902. Saint-Pierre, known as the \"Paris of the West Indies\", was in the direct path of a [[pyroclastic flow]], which destroyed the city and killed an estimated 30,000 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubs.er.usgs.gov/publication/ofr87297|title=Volcanic hazards with regard to siting nuclear-power plants in the Pacific Northwest|date=1987|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref>\n\nSylbaris later travelled with the [[Ringling Brothers and Barnum and Bailey Circus|Barnum & Bailey]] [[circus]] and became something of an early 20th-century celebrity.\n\n==Saint-Pierre and the eruption==\n\n[[File:Prison Saint-Pierre Martinique.JPG|thumb|Remains of the cell in which Sylbaris survived]]\n\nLudger Sylbaris was born on 1 June 1874, on the ''Habitation La Donneau'' plantation, near the fishing village of Le Pr\u00eacheur, Martinique, about {{convert|9|km|mi}} north of Saint-Pierre. It is commonly believed that his birth name was either August Cyparis or Louis-Auguste Cyparis, but his actual birth record belies this interpretation.<ref>[http://anom.archivesnationales.culture.gouv.fr/caomec2/osd.php?territoire=MARTINIQUE&commune=LE%20PRECHEUR&annee=1874&typeacte=AC_RE Civil Archives of Le Pr\u00eacheur, Martinique], 1874, record #124, Sylbaris, Ludger</ref> Sylbaris worked as a common labourer in the capital city, [[Saint-Pierre, Martinique|Saint-Pierre]], in the shadow of the volcano [[Mount Pel\u00e9e]].\n\nOn the night of 7 May 1902, the night before the eruption, Sylbaris got involved in either a bar fight or a street brawl, according to various sources, and was thrown into jail overnight for assault. Some accounts claim that Sylbaris actually killed a man and was thrown into jail for murder,{{fact|date=June 2019}} although it is unknown if this is the correct version of events. Many sources indicate Sylbaris was frequently in trouble with the authorities. Some fictional accounts state that he had a [[precognitive dreams|precognitive dream]] and was locked up as a drunk after causing a riot.<ref>[[Leo Dorfman|Dorfman, Leo]]. \"The Yawning Mouth of Hell.\" Comic strip. DC Special Blue Ribbon Digest No.6 - reprinted from ''[[Ghosts (comics)|Ghosts]]''. Vol. 2. New York, NY: DC Comics Inc, 1981. 26-29.</ref>\n\nWhatever the cause of his arrest, Sylbaris was ordered to be put into [[solitary confinement]] and locked in a single-cell, bomb-proof magazine with stone walls that was built partially underground. The cell did not have windows and was ventilated only through a narrow grating in the door facing away from the volcano. His prison was the most sheltered building in the city, and it was this fact that saved his life. The cell in which he survived still stands today.\n\nAt 7:52 AM on May 8, the upper mountainside of Mount Pel\u00e9e tore open, causing a dense black cloud to shoot out horizontally. A second black cloud rolled upwards as a column of ash and rock, forming a gigantic mushroom plume that darkened the sky within a {{convert|50|mi|km|adj=on}} radius. The initial speed of both clouds was later calculated at more than {{convert|670|kph|mph|abbr=on}}. The vertical cloud plunged down the western slope of the volcano, raced down at 161 kilometers per hour, and destroyed Saint-Pierre in less than a minute. The devastated area by the [[pyroclastic flow]] covered about {{convert|21|km2|abbr=on}}, with the city of Saint-Pierre taking its full brunt. The cloud consisted of superheated gases and fine debris, with searing temperatures of over {{convert|1000|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}. All of the city's infrastructure was flattened, and almost the entire population burned or suffocated.\n\nFour days after the eruption, a rescue team heard Sylbaris' cries from the rubble of the prison. Although badly burned, he survived and was able to provide an account of the event. According to his account, at about breakfast time on the day of the eruption, it grew very dark. Hot air mixed with fine ashes entered his cell through the door grating, despite his efforts in urinating on his clothing and stuffing it in the door. The heat lasted only a short moment, enough to cause deep burns on Sylbaris' hands, arms, legs, and back, but his clothes did not ignite, and he avoided breathing the searing hot air.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/prelude-doomsday |title=Prelude to Doomsday |first=Lately |last=Thomas |date=August 1961 |volume=12 |issue=5 |magazine=American Heritage Magazine}}</ref>\n\nThe only other survivors in the town were [[L\u00e9on Comp\u00e8re-L\u00e9andre]], a shoemaker whose house was on the very edge of the path of the pyroclastic flows, and Havivra Da Ifrile, a young girl who ran from the eruption, got into a boat and survived when she was washed out to sea, unconscious.\n\n==Later life==\n\nSylbaris was pardoned of his crimes and later joined [[Ringling Brothers and Barnum and Bailey Circus|Barnum & Bailey]]'s circus, touring America and recounting the horrors of the explosion. He became a minor celebrity in the process, advertised as \"the man who lived through Doomsday\" or \"the Most Marvelous Man in the World\". He was the first black man ever to star in Barnum and Bailey's \"Greatest Show on Earth\", which at the time was a segregated show.{{fact|date=June 2019}} He could be seen in a replica of his cell in Saint-Pierre.<ref>[http://www.texashiking.com/Links/Details.asp?asin=1582341990 Texas Hiking article]{{Dead link|date=August 2009|fix-attempted=yes}} for Fire Mountain, {{ISBN|978-1582341996}}</ref>\n\nSylbaris died of [[natural causes]] in 1929.\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [http://www.geology.sdsu.edu/how_volcanoes_work/Thumblinks/Sampson_page.html Barnum and Bailey Poster]\n* [http://www.geology.sdsu.edu/how_volcanoes_work/Pelee.html Mt. Pel\u00e9e Eruption (1902)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050409210339/http://library.thinkquest.org/26568/pelee.htm Thinkquest.org article]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sylbaris, Ludger}}\n[[Category:Martiniquais criminals]]\n[[Category:Sole survivors]]\n[[Category:Recipients of French presidential pardons]]\n[[Category:1874 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Cyparis.jpg|thumb|270px|right|A postcard featuring Sylbaris/Cyparis labelled \"survivor of Saint-Pierre\".]]\n\n'''Ludger Sylbaris''' (1 June 1874<ref>[[Peter Morgan|Morgan, Peter]]. Fire Mountain, {{ISBN | 1-58234-199-0}}, Bloomsbury. New York, NY: 2003. 42-43.</ref> &ndash; {{c.}} 1929) was an [[Afro-Caribbean]] man who was one of two survivors in the city of [[Saint-Pierre, Martinique|Saint-Pierre]] on the Caribbean island of [[Martinique]] during the [[Mount Pel\u00e9e#1902 eruption|devastating volcanic eruption of Mount Pelee]] on May 8, 1902. Saint-Pierre, known as the \"Paris of the West Indies\", was in the direct path of a [[pyroclastic flow]], which destroyed the city and killed an estimated 30,000 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubs.er.usgs.gov/publication/ofr87297|title=Volcanic hazards with regard to siting nuclear-power plants in the Pacific Northwest|date=1987|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref>\n\nSylbaris later travelled with the [[Ringling Brothers and Barnum and Bailey Circus|Barnum & Bailey]] [[circus]] and became something of an early 20th-century celebrity.\n\n==Saint-Pierre and the eruption==\n\n[[File:Prison Saint-Pierre Martinique.JPG|thumb|Remains of the cell in which Sylbaris survived]]\n\nLudger Sylbaris was born on 1 June 1874, on the ''Habitation La Donneau'' plantation, near the fishing village of Le Pr\u00eacheur, Martinique, about {{convert|9|km|mi}} north of Saint-Pierre. It is commonly believed that his birth name was either August Cyparis or Louis-Auguste Cyparis, but his actual birth record belies this interpretation.<ref>[http://anom.archivesnationales.culture.gouv.fr/caomec2/osd.php?territoire=MARTINIQUE&commune=LE%20PRECHEUR&annee=1874&typeacte=AC_RE Civil Archives of Le Pr\u00eacheur, Martinique], 1874, record #124, Sylbaris, Ludger</ref> Sylbaris worked as a common labourer in the capital city, [[Saint-Pierre, Martinique|Saint-Pierre]], in the shadow of the volcano [[Mount Pel\u00e9e]].\n\nOn the night of 7 May 1902, the night before the eruption, Sylbaris got involved in either a bar fight or a street brawl, according to various sources, and was thrown into jail overnight for assault. Some accounts claim that Sylbaris actually killed a man and was thrown into jail for murder,{{fact|date=June 2019}} although it is unknown if this is the correct version of events. Many sources indicate Sylbaris was frequently in trouble with the authorities. Some fictional accounts state that he had a [[precognitive dreams|precognitive dream]] and was locked up as a drunk after causing a riot.<ref>[[Leo Dorfman|Dorfman, Leo]]. \"The Yawning Mouth of Hell.\" Comic strip. DC Special Blue Ribbon Digest No.6 - reprinted from ''[[Ghosts (comics)|Ghosts]]''. Vol. 2. New York, NY: DC Comics Inc, 1981. 26-29.</ref>\n\nWhatever the cause of his arrest, Sylbaris was ordered to be put into [[solitary confinement]] and locked in a single-cell, bomb-proof magazine with stone walls that was built partially underground. The cell did not have windows and was ventilated only through a narrow grating in the door facing away from the volcano. His prison was the most sheltered building in the city, and it was this fact that saved his life. The cell in which he survived still stands today.\n\nAt 7:52 AM on May 8, the upper mountainside of Mount Pel\u00e9e tore open, causing a dense black cloud to shoot out horizontally. A second black cloud rolled upwards as a column of ash and rock, forming a gigantic mushroom plume that darkened the sky within a {{convert|50|mi|km|adj=on}} radius. The initial speed of both clouds was later calculated at more than {{convert|670|kph|mph|abbr=on}}. The vertical cloud plunged down the western slope of the volcano, raced down at 161 kilometers per hour, and destroyed Saint-Pierre in less than a minute. The devastated area by the [[pyroclastic flow]] covered about {{convert|21|km2|abbr=on}}, with the city of Saint-Pierre taking its full brunt. The cloud consisted of superheated gases and fine debris, with searing temperatures of over {{convert|1000|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}. All of the city's infrastructure was flattened, and almost the entire population burned or suffocated.\n\nFour days after the eruption, a rescue team heard Sylbaris' cries from the rubble of the prison. Although badly burned, he survived and was able to provide an account of the event. According to his account, at about breakfast time on the day of the eruption, it grew very dark. Hot air mixed with fine ashes entered his cell through the door grating, despite his efforts in urinating on his clothing and stuffing it in the door. The heat lasted only a short moment, enough to cause deep burns on Sylbaris' hands, arms, legs, and back, but his clothes did not ignite, and he avoided breathing the searing hot air.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/prelude-doomsday |title=Prelude to Doomsday |first=Lately |last=Thomas |date=August 1961 |volume=12 |issue=5 |magazine=American Heritage Magazine}}</ref>\n\nThe only other survivors in the town were [[L\u00e9on Comp\u00e8re-L\u00e9andre]], a shoemaker whose house was on the very edge of the path of the pyroclastic flows, and Havivra Da Ifrile, a young girl who ran from the eruption, got into a boat and survived when she was washed out to sea, unconscious.\n\n==Later life==\n\nSylbaris was pardoned of his crimes and later joined [[Ringling Brothers and Barnum and Bailey Circus|Barnum & Bailey]]'s circus, touring America and recounting the horrors of the explosion. He became a minor celebrity in the process, advertised as \"the man who lived through Doomsday\" or \"the Most Marvelous Man in the World\". He was the first black man ever to star in Barnum and Bailey's \"Greatest Show on Earth\", which at the time was a segregated show.{{fact|date=June 2019}} He could be seen in a replica of his cell in Saint-Pierre.<ref>[http://www.texashiking.com/Links/Details.asp?asin=1582341990 Texas Hiking article]{{Dead link|date=August 2009|fix-attempted=yes}} for Fire Mountain, {{ISBN|978-1582341996}}</ref>\n\nSylbaris died of [[natural causes]] in 1929.\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [http://www.geology.sdsu.edu/how_volcanoes_work/Thumblinks/Sampson_page.html Barnum and Bailey Poster]\n* [http://www.geology.sdsu.edu/how_volcanoes_work/Pelee.html Mt. Pel\u00e9e Eruption (1902)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050409210339/http://library.thinkquest.org/26568/pelee.htm Thinkquest.org article]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sylbaris, Ludger}}\n[[Category:Martiniquais criminals]]\n[[Category:Sole survivors]]\n[[Category:Recipients of French presidential pardons]]\n[[Category:1874 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "2605:6001:e7c4:1e00:e85f:36b4:a5b4:97fb", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ludger_Sylbaris"}
{"title_page": "Samir Loussif", "text_new": "{{short description|Tunisian Mezwed singer}}\n\n{{infobox musical artist\n| name             = Samir Loussif\n| native_name      = \u0633\u0645\u064a\u0631 \u0644\u0648\u0633\u064a\u0641\n| native_name_lang = Arabic\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| landscape        = yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = \n| origin           = Tunisian\n| occupation       = Singer, composer\n| instrument       = \n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Samir Loussif''' ({{lang-ar|\u0633\u0645\u064a\u0631 \u0644\u0648\u0635\u064a\u0641}}) is a [[Tunisia|Tunisian]] [[Mezwed]] [[Singing|singer]].\n\n== Biography ==\n\nAt one time, it was banned from broadcasting on Tunisian television as well as other mezoued artists.\n\nSamir Loussif is a variety singer\u00a0 , he sings a large repertoire inspired by Tunisian folk art. Her songs express pain or hope, her melodies are refined and the lyrics are poetic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://repertoire-artistestunisiens.com/samir-loussif/|title=Samir Loussif -|date=2016-09-30|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nHis popular song is titled \"''ya mimti el ghalia''\" which roughly means \"oh my mother, so dear\". This song with a soft and melancholic rhythm tells the story of a man who sings to his mother and who tells him how much he misses her and how difficult it is to live abroad . This song is very successful for Tunisians living abroad in particular are much more likely to feel this poetry. \"''Ya mimti el ghalia''\" (Oh my mother, so dear), \"''Ya 'in min' ineya''\" (the apple of my eye).\n\n== Discography ==\n\n* ''Face A Face''\n* ''Ghayedhni Omri''\n* ''J'en Ai Marre''\n* ''Ma Troumaha Layam''\n* ''Maadhour''\n* ''Ya Galbi''\n* ''Ya Mimty L'ghalya''\n* ''Ya Warda''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loussif, Samir}}\n[[Category:Tunisian singers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Tunisian people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Tunisia-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-singer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Tunisian Mezwed singer}}\n\n{{infobox musical artist\n| name             = Samir Loussif\n| native_name      = \u0633\u0645\u064a\u0631 \u0644\u0648\u0633\u064a\u0641\n| native_name_lang = Arabic\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| landscape        = yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = \n| origin           = Tunisian\n| occupation       = Singer, composer\n| instrument       = \n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Samir Loussif''' ({{lang-ar|\u0633\u0645\u064a\u0631 \u0644\u0648\u0635\u064a\u0641}}) is a [[Tunisia|Tunisian]] [[Mezwed]] [[Singing|singer]].\n\n== Biography ==\n\nAt one time, it was banned from broadcasting on Tunisian television as well as other mezoued artists.\n\nSamir Loussif is a variety singer\u00a0 , he sings a large repertoire inspired by Tunisian folk art. Her songs express pain or hope, her melodies are refined and the lyrics are poetic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://repertoire-artistestunisiens.com/samir-loussif/|title=Samir Loussif -|date=2016-09-30|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nHis popular song is titled \"''ya mimti el ghalia''\" which roughly means \"oh my mother, so dear\". This song with a soft and melancholic rhythm tells the story of a man who sings to his mother and who tells him how much he misses her and how difficult it is to live abroad ... This song is very successful for Tunisians living abroad in particular are much more likely to feel this poetry. \"''Ya mimti el ghalia''\" (Oh my mother, so dear), \"''Ya 'in min' ineya''\" (the apple of my eye).\n\n== Discography ==\n\n* ''Face A Face''\n* ''Ghayedhni Omri''\n* ''J'en Ai Marre''\n* ''Ma Troumaha Layam''\n* ''Maadhour''\n* ''Ya Galbi''\n* ''Ya Mimty L'ghalya''\n* ''Ya Warda''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loussif, Samir}}\n[[Category:Tunisian singers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Tunisian people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Tunisia-bio-stub}}\n{{Africa-singer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Eyatu Ben", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samir_Loussif"}
{"title_page": "State Highway 3 (New Zealand)", "text_new": "{{short description|Road in New Zealand}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=June 2015}}\n{{infobox road\n| country = NZL\n| type = SH\n| route = 3\n| map = NZ-SH3 map.png\n| length_km = 500\n| direction_a = North\n| direction_b = South\n| terminus_a = [[File:State Highway 1 NZ.svg|20px]] [[New Zealand State Highway 1|SH 1]] at [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]\n| junction = \n| destinations = [[Te Awamutu]], [[Otorohanga]], [[Te Kuiti]], [[New Plymouth]], [[Hawera]], [[Whanganui]], [[Palmerston North]] Woodville\n| terminus_b = [[File:State Highway 2 NZ.svg|20px]] [[New Zealand State Highway 2|SH 2]] at [[Woodville, New Zealand|Woodville]]\n| previous_type = SH\n| previous_route = 2\n| next_type = SH\n| next_route = 4\n}}\n\n'''State Highway 3''' ('''SH&nbsp;3''') is one of [[New Zealand]]'s eight [[New Zealand state highway network|national state highways]]. It serves the west coast of the country's [[North Island]] and forms a link between [[New Zealand State Highway 1|State Highway 1]] and [[New Zealand State Highway 2|State Highway 2]]. Distances are measured from north to south.\n\nFor most of its length SH 3 is a two-lane single carriageway, with at-grade intersections and property accesses, both in rural and urban areas.\n\n== History ==\nA [[Mokau]] \u2013 [[Awakino]] horse track was widened to a dray track about 1897.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH18970621.2.21&srpos=23&zto=1|title=Communication Between Auckland And Taranaki.|date=1897-06-21|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=5|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> It was then possible for a horse and buggy to cover the {{Convert|110|mi||abbr=on}} \u2013 now 162&nbsp;km \u2013 from New Plymouth to Te Kuiti in 17\u00bd hours.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TH19020411.2.2|title=Overland to Auckland.|date=1902-04-11|work=Taranaki Herald|access-date=2018-02-16|pages=1}}</ref> The first car to traverse the route from Auckland to New Plymouth seems to have been an 8&nbsp;hp Cadillac in 1905, though Otorohanga to Te Kuiti was by [[North Island Main Trunk|train]] and, between Awakino and Mokau, a horse assisted on the beach.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19050405.2.86&srpos=10&zto=1|title=Through King Country On A Motor.|date=1905-04-05|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=6|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\nA 1910 Te Kuiti meeting called for [[Gravel road|metalling]] of the road to Awakino.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=WAIGUS19100118.2.28&zto=1|title=King Country Roads.|date=1910-01-18|newspaper=Waikato Argus|pages=4|access-date=2016-05-28}}</ref> '''Mt Messenger tunnel''' opened in 1916 and its single lane was enlarged about 1983.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/taranaki_tunnels/topics/show/1135-mt-messenger-tunnel-shw-3|title=Mt Messenger Tunnel \u2013 SHW 3|last=Ron|website=ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> \u00a33,000 (2016 equivalent $280,000)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rbnz.govt.nz/monetary-policy/inflation-calculator|title=Inflation calculator \u2013 Reserve Bank of New Zealand|website=www.rbnz.govt.nz|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> was provided in 1919<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=TDN19191025.2.7&srpos=13&zto=1|title=Public Works Estimates.|date=1919-10-25|newspaper=Taranaki Daily News|pages=2|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> for the '''Awakino Gorge''' section, including the tunnel (enlarged in 2011),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nzta.govt.nz/media-releases/works-planned-to-trim-back-the-inside-walls-of-the-awakino-tunnel-on-state-highway-3/|title=Works planned to trim back the inside walls of the Awakino Tunnel on State Highway 3 NZ Transport Agency|website=www.nzta.govt.nz|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> and it was opened in March 1923 at a total cost of about \u00a360,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19230331.2.114&srpos=3265&zto=1|title=Link With Taranaxi.|date=1923-03-31|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=10|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> (2016 equivalent $5.8m).<ref name=\":0\" /> Most of the route was gazetted as a government main highway in 1924,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=EP19240613.2.139&srpos=15&zto=1|title=Main Roads|date=1924-06-13|newspaper=Evening Post|pages=10|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> some sections were tar-sealed in 1925<ref name=\"Road To Taranaki\">{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19250507.2.39&srpos=3333&zto=1|title=Road To Taranaki.|date=1925-05-07|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=8|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> and more work had been done on the road by 1936, leaving only a few mud sections.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19361019.2.114&zto=1|title=Better Roads|date=1936-10-19|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=10|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> By 1949 the road was sealed as far south as Te Kuiti and the reinforced concrete bridge over the Waipa at Otorohanga had been started.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://atojs.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/atojs?a=d&d=AJHR1949-I.2.2.3.1&pg=51|title=AtoJs Online \u2014 Appendix to the Journals of the House of Representatives \u2014 1949 Session I  \u2014 D-01 MINISTRY OF WORKS STATEMENT (BY THE HON. R. SEMPLE, MINISTER OF WORKS)|website=atojs.natlib.govt.nz|page=53|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n[[File:Mokau Bridge.jpg|left|thumb|Mokau Bridge opened 1927]]\nThe {{Convert|12|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide, single-lane,<ref name=\"Road To Taranaki\"/> 11-span, {{Convert|670|ft|m|abbr=on}}, steel,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19250706.2.42&srpos=3358&zto=1|title=Mokau River Bridge.|date=1925-07-06|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=8|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> '''Mokau Bridge'''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19271217.2.44&srpos=3496&zto=1|title=Mokau River Bridge.|date=1927-12-17|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=12|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> opened in October 1927<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=NZH19271017.2.11.7&zto=1|title=Main Highway From Auckland To Taranaki Now Completed: The Mokau River Bridge Open For Traffic Photographs Taken On Friday Last. Left: A View From The Bridge Showing Cars Waiting For The Lift-span In The Middle Of The Structure To Be Lowered. Right: A General View Of The New Bridge, Which Eliminates The Ancient Ferry-punt So Well Known To Travellers On Thete Kuiti-new Plymouth Section Of The Route. The Opening Of The Bridge Will Expedite Overland Travel And Incidentally Enable The New ' ' Zealand Herald To Reach New Plymouth Earlier Every Day.|date=1927-10-17|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=6|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> (official opening 17 December), replacing a [[Cable ferry|punt]]. The cost was \u00a335,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=CHP19271219.2.63&srpos=3498&zto=1|title=Mokau Bridge Opened.|date=1927-12-19|newspaper=Press|pages=10|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> (2016 equivalent $3.3m).<ref name=\":0\" /> It had a lifting span allowing passage of vessels up to {{Convert|50|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide and with a {{Convert|60|ft|m|abbr=on}} clearance at high tide.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2001 the 1927 bridge was replaced by the current 9-span, {{Convert|230|m|yd|abbr=on}}, double lane, [[Prestressed concrete|pre-stressed concrete]] bridge for $6.2m<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smithbridge.net/projects/item/mokau-bridge.html|title=Mokau Bridge \u2013 Smithbridge|website=www.smithbridge.net|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> (2016 equivalent $8.5m).<ref name=\":0\" /> The new bridge doesn't allow for shipping, as the first ship to pass under the old lifting span was withdrawn three months after the bridge opened.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/taranaki-daily-news/news/9381752/The-story-of-the-steamer-Wetere|title=The story of the steamer Wetere|last=Duckett|first=Graeme|date=2013-11-09|newspaper=Stuff.co.nz|language=English|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref>\n\nAn 1871 account of a coach journey from New Plymouth to Wellington described the very poor road round the coast via [[Opunake]] to [[Whanganui]] and the much better and well used road south from there. A government subsidy of \u00a33,000 (2016 equivalent $400,000)<ref name=\":0\" /> a year was being paid for the coach north of Whanganui.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=TH18710802.2.16&srpos=15&zto=1|title=New Plymouth To Wellington\" Overland.|date=1871-08-02|newspaper=Taranaki Herald|pages=2|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref>\n\n==Route==\n[[File:Awakino tunnel.jpg|thumb|left|Tunnel at the north end of the Awakino Gorge. There is another short tunnel near the top of Mount Messenger]]\nThe highway leaves SH 1 at Hamilton, and initially heads south through farmland, passing through [[Te Awamutu]]. Sections of this stretch of the road are four-laned, but not divided carriageway. From [[Otorohanga]] it follows the valley of the [[Waipa River]] to [[Te Kuiti]]. The road then turns southwest through sparsely settled farmland, crossing several ridges before following the Awakino gorge to reach the coast, which it follows around the North Taranaki Bight. At the [[Tongaporutu River]] the highway turns inland to avoid coastal cliffs and climbs over Mount Messenger before descending via the [[Mimi River (New Zealand)|Mimi River]] valley to return to the coast near [[Urenui]]. Bypassing [[Waitara, New Zealand|Waitara]], it reaches [[New Plymouth]] then turns inland, passing to the east of [[Mount Taranaki]] via [[Inglewood, New Zealand|Inglewood]], [[Stratford, New Zealand|Stratford]] and [[Eltham, New Zealand|Eltham]] to [[Hawera]].\n\nFrom Hawera the highway follows the coast of the South Taranaki Bight southeastwards to [[Patea]] and [[Whanganui]] before meeting SH 1 again at [[Bulls, New Zealand|Bulls]]. SH 1 and 3 share their route for 6&nbsp;km as they cross the [[Rangitikei River]] to [[Sanson, New Zealand|Sanson]], where SH 3 continues southeast towards [[Palmerston North]]. After crossing the [[Manawatu River]], the route follows its south bank through the [[Manawatu Gorge]] to its terminus and junction with [[New Zealand State Highway 2|SH 2]] at [[Woodville, New Zealand|Woodville]] in the [[Tararua District]]\n\nBoth the Awakino and Manawatu gorges are prone to closure by slips and rockslides in heavy rain.\n\n==Route changes==\nConstruction of a bypass of [[Bell Block, Taranaki|Bell Block]], a satellite town of New Plymouth, was completed in 2010. The bypass is a four-lane, divided expressway with an interchange at Henwood Road providing access to Bell Block.<ref name=\"Stuff.co.nz_3438349\">{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/taranaki-daily-news/news/3438349/Bypass-ready-to-roll |title=Bypass ready to roll |author=Maetzig, Rob |date=12 March 2010 |work=[[Taranaki Daily News]] |accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, a section of SH 3 in Taranaki was realigned replacing the \"deadly\" [[Normanby, Taranaki|Normanby]] overbridge.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/taranaki-daily-news/news/85389029/normanby-overbridge-bypass-ready-for-use-from-monday |title=Normanby overbridge bypass ready for use from Monday |author=David Burroughs |work=Taranaki Daily News |date=16 October 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Future improvements==\nOn 27 January 2016, funding was announced for road bypasses of the two tunnels north of [[New Plymouth]]. Construction of the Mount Messenger and Awakino Gorge tunnel bypasses was expected to begin within two years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/politics/news/article.cfm?c_id=280&objectid=11580485 |title=Key's state of the nation \u2013 full speech |accessdate=2016-01-27 |publisher=NZHerald.co.nz}}</ref>\n\nState Highway 3 will also form part of the future/proposed Southern Links motorway project in the South/West of Hamilton and Tamahere.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzta.govt.nz/projects/southern-links |title=Southern Links |publisher=NZTA.govt.nz}}</ref>\n\nThe highway through the [[Manawatu Gorge]] between [[Ashhurst]] and [[Woodville, New Zealand|Woodville]] in the [[Manawatu-Wanganui|Manawatu Whanganui Region]] was closed in April 2017 due to a large slip, with SH 3 traffic diverted via Saddle Road. Contractors were pulled out of clearing the slip in July 2017 due to ongoing geological movement in the hill, closing the road indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11887257|title=Manawatu Gorge to remain closed 'for some time'|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2017-07-10|language=en-NZ}}</ref> The NZTA is fast-tracking a long-term solution to bypass and replace the gorge, although it is not expected to be in place before 2023. \n\nOther improvements include:\n*An upgrade of SH 3 in New Plymouth from Vickers Road to the city<ref name=\"Taranakiinvestments\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nzta.govt.nz/planning-and-investment/2015-18-national-land-transport-programme/nltp-in-the-regions/taranaki/#key-routes |title=Taranaki key routes and investments |work=NZ Transport Agency |accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Spur sections==\n{{infobox road small\n|country=NZL\n|type=SH\n|route=3A\n|length_km=15.6\n|length_round=1\n|location=SH 3 west of Waitara \u2013 SH 3 at Inglewood\n}}\nSH 3 has one spur, designated State Highway 3A. This 15.6&nbsp;km stretch links State Highway 3 just west of Waitara to Inglewood, providing a shortcut and bypass of New Plymouth. The entire length of highway carries the name Mountain Road with the sole exception being a very short link of Rata Street in Inglewood to rejoin SH 3.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Major junctions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Territorial authorities of New Zealand|Territorial authority]] !! Location !! km !! jct !! Destinations !! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton City]] || rowspan=2| Melville || 0 || [[File:New Zealand road sign W10-4.svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|1|dir1=north|name1=Kahikatea Drive}} \u2013 [[Auckland]]<br>{{jct|country=NZL|SH|1|dir1=south|name1=Lorne Street}} \u2013 [[Rotorua]], [[Taupo]] || ''SH 3 begins''\n|-\n| 1 || [[File:New Zealand road sign W11-1.svg|25px]] || Normandy Ave \u2013 [[Hamilton, New Zealand|City Centre]], [[Rotorua]] || to {{jct|country=NZL|SH|1}}/[[Thermal Explorer Highway]] south\n|-\n| [[Waipa District]] || [[Hamilton Airport (New Zealand)|Hamilton Airport]] || 10 || [[File:New Zealand road sign W11-1.svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|21|name1=Airport Road}} \u2013 [[Hamilton Airport (New Zealand)|Airport]], [[Mystery Creek Events Centre|Mystery Creek]] ||The roundabout  was completed in June 2016 at a cost about $4.5 million to improve safety, after five deaths in five years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nzta.govt.nz/projects/sh3-sh21-intersection-improvement|title=SH3/21 Intersection improvement|website=www.nzta.govt.nz|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-12-07}}</ref>\n|- \n| [[Otorohanga|Otorohanga District]] || Otorohanga || 55 || [[File:New Zealand PW-11 (right).svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|31|SH|39}} (Te Kanawa Street) \u2013 [[Kawhia]], [[Ng\u0101ruaw\u0101hia]]  || Alternative route to Auckland, bypassing Hamilton\n|-\n| rowspan=3| [[Waitomo District]] || Hangatiki || 65 || [[File:New Zealand road sign W11-1.svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|37|name1=Waitomo Caves Road}} \u2013 [[Waitomo Caves]] ||The $3.6 million roundabout opened in June 2015,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nzta.govt.nz/media-releases/work-wrapping-up-on-new-king-country-roundabout/|title=Work wrapping up on new King Country roundabout|website=www.nzta.govt.nz|access-date=2018-12-07}}</ref> about {{Convert|60|m||abbr=on}} north of the previous junction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nzta.govt.nz/projects/sh3sh37-waitomo-intersection/|title=SH3/SH37 Waitomo Intersection|website=www.nzta.govt.nz|access-date=2018-12-07}}</ref> It followed two deaths in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/news/69255584/nzta-to-finish-waitomo-caves-roundabout|title=NZTA to finish Waitomo Caves roundabout|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2018-12-07}}</ref>\n|-  \n| [[Te Kuiti]] || 76 || [[File:New Zealand road sign R2-2.svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|30|name1=Awakino Road}} \u2013 [[Rotorua]], [[Taupo]] ||\n|-\n| Eight Mile Junction || 88 || [[File:New Zealand PW-11 (left).svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|4}} \u2013 [[Taumarunui]], [[National Park, New Zealand|National Park]] ||\n|-\n| rowspan=4| [[New Plymouth|New Plymouth District]] || Brixton || 229 || [[File:New Zealand PW-11 (left).svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|3A|name1=Mountain Road|nolink1=y}} \u2013 [[Inglewood, New Zealand|Inglewood]], [[Whanganui]] || Alternative route to Southern Taranaki, bypassing New Plymouth\n|-\n| rowspan=2| New Plymouth || rowspan=2| 240 || [[File:New Zealand road sign W10-4.svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|44|name1=Eliot Street}} \u2013 [[Port Taranaki]]<br>{{jct|country=NZL|SH|45|dir1=eastbound|name1=Courtenay Street}} || rowspan=2|\n|-\n| [[File:New Zealand road sign W10-4.svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|45|dir1=westbound|name1=Leach Street}} \u2013 City Centre, [[Opunake]]\n|-\n| [[Inglewood, New Zealand|Inglewood]] || 258 || [[File:New Zealand PW-9.1 (right).svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|3A|name1=Rata Street|nolink1=y}} \u2013 [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] || Alternative route to [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]], bypassing New Plymouth\n|-\n| [[Stratford, New Zealand|Stratford District]] || Stratford || 279 || [[File:New Zealand road sign W11-1.svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|43|name1=Regan Street}} \u2013 [[Taumarunui]] ||\n|-\n| [[South Taranaki District]] || [[Hawera]] || 310 || [[File:New Zealand road sign R2-2.svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|45|name1=South Road}} \u2013 [[Opunake]] ||\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | [[Whanganui District]] || Whanganui || rowspan=2 | 402 || [[File:New Zealand PW-44.svg|25px]] || ''[[Whanganui River]]'' ||\n|-\n| Putiki || [[File:New Zealand road sign W11-1.svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|4|name1=Putiki Drive}} \u2013 City Centre, [[National Park, New Zealand|National Park]] <br /> Wikitoria Road \u2013 [[Whanganui Airport]] ||\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[Rangitikei District]] || rowspan=3| [[Bulls, New Zealand|Bulls]] || 445 || [[File:New Zealand PW-11 (left).svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|1|dir1=north|name1=High Street}} \u2013 [[Taupo]] || SH 1/SH 3 concurrency begins\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 447 || [[File:New Zealand PW-44.svg|25px]] || rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[Rangitikei River]]'' || rowspan=2| \n|-\n| rowspan=3| [[Manawatu District]]\n|-\n| [[Sanson, New Zealand|Sanson]] || 450 || [[File:New Zealand PW-11 (right).svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|1|dir1=south|name1=Wellington Road}} \u2013 [[Wellington]] || SH 1/SH 3 concurrency ends\n|-\n| Newbury || 468 || [[File:New Zealand PW-11 (left).svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|54|name1=Kairanga Bunnythorpe Road}} \u2013 [[Feilding]] ||\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[Palmerston North|Palmerston North City]] || rowspan=2| [[Ashhurst]] || rowspan=2| 488 || [[File:New Zealand PW-44.svg|25px]] || ''[[Manawatu River]]'' ||\n|-\n| [[File:New Zealand PW-11 (right).svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|57|name1=Fitzherbert East Road}} \u2013 [[Levin, New Zealand|Levin]] ||\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[Tararua District]] || || 495 || [[File:New Zealand PW-44.svg|25px]] || ''Manawatu River'' ||\n|-\n| [[Woodville, New Zealand|Woodville]] || 500 || [[File:New Zealand PW-11 (right).svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|2|dir1=north|name1=Vogel Street}} \u2013 [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]] <br /> {{jct|country=NZL|SH|2|dir1=south|name1=McLean Street}} \u2013 [[Masterton]], [[Wellington]] || ''SH 3 ends''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of New Zealand state highways]]\n* [[List of roads and highways]], for notable or famous roads worldwide\n* [[Public transport in Hamilton and Waikato#SH3 routes to Te Awamutu and south west - current route 24|Public transport in Hamilton and Waikato]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://nzta.govt.nz/ New Zealand Transport Agency]\n*[https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/parliamentary/appendix-to-the-journals-of-the-house-of-representatives/1924/I/2250 1923 photo of steam roller completing Awakino tunnel]\n*[http://collections.lib.uwm.edu/digital/collection/agsoceania/id/293 1924 photo of Awakino tunnel]\n{{New Zealand State Highway navbox}}\n\n[[Category:State Highways in New Zealand|3]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=June 2015}}\n{{infobox road\n| country = NZL\n| type = SH\n| route = 3\n| map = NZ-SH3 map.png\n| length_km = 500\n| direction_a = North\n| direction_b = South\n| terminus_a = [[File:State Highway 1 NZ.svg|20px]] [[New Zealand State Highway 1|SH 1]] at [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]\n| junction = \n| destinations = [[Te Awamutu]], [[Otorohanga]], [[Te Kuiti]], [[New Plymouth]], [[Hawera]], [[Whanganui]], [[Palmerston North]] Woodville\n| terminus_b = [[File:State Highway 2 NZ.svg|20px]] [[New Zealand State Highway 2|SH 2]] at [[Woodville, New Zealand|Woodville]]\n| previous_type = SH\n| previous_route = 2\n| next_type = SH\n| next_route = 4\n}}\n\n'''State Highway 3''' ('''SH&nbsp;3''') is one of [[New Zealand]]'s eight [[New Zealand state highway network|national state highways]]. It serves the west coast of the country's [[North Island]] and forms a link between [[New Zealand State Highway 1|State Highway 1]] and [[New Zealand State Highway 2|State Highway 2]]. Distances are measured from north to south.\n\nFor most of its length SH 3 is a two-lane single carriageway, with at-grade intersections and property accesses, both in rural and urban areas.\n\n== History ==\nA [[Mokau]] \u2013 [[Awakino]] horse track was widened to a dray track about 1897.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH18970621.2.21&srpos=23&zto=1|title=Communication Between Auckland And Taranaki.|date=1897-06-21|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=5|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> It was then possible for a horse and buggy to cover the {{Convert|110|mi||abbr=on}} \u2013 now 162&nbsp;km \u2013 from New Plymouth to Te Kuiti in 17\u00bd hours.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TH19020411.2.2|title=Overland to Auckland.|date=1902-04-11|work=Taranaki Herald|access-date=2018-02-16|pages=1}}</ref> The first car to traverse the route from Auckland to New Plymouth seems to have been an 8&nbsp;hp Cadillac in 1905, though Otorohanga to Te Kuiti was by [[North Island Main Trunk|train]] and, between Awakino and Mokau, a horse assisted on the beach.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19050405.2.86&srpos=10&zto=1|title=Through King Country On A Motor.|date=1905-04-05|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=6|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\nA 1910 Te Kuiti meeting called for [[Gravel road|metalling]] of the road to Awakino.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=WAIGUS19100118.2.28&zto=1|title=King Country Roads.|date=1910-01-18|newspaper=Waikato Argus|pages=4|access-date=2016-05-28}}</ref> '''Mt Messenger tunnel''' opened in 1916 and its single lane was enlarged about 1983.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/taranaki_tunnels/topics/show/1135-mt-messenger-tunnel-shw-3|title=Mt Messenger Tunnel \u2013 SHW 3|last=Ron|website=ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> \u00a33,000 (2016 equivalent $280,000)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rbnz.govt.nz/monetary-policy/inflation-calculator|title=Inflation calculator \u2013 Reserve Bank of New Zealand|website=www.rbnz.govt.nz|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> was provided in 1919<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=TDN19191025.2.7&srpos=13&zto=1|title=Public Works Estimates.|date=1919-10-25|newspaper=Taranaki Daily News|pages=2|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> for the '''Awakino Gorge''' section, including the tunnel (enlarged in 2011),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nzta.govt.nz/media-releases/works-planned-to-trim-back-the-inside-walls-of-the-awakino-tunnel-on-state-highway-3/|title=Works planned to trim back the inside walls of the Awakino Tunnel on State Highway 3 NZ Transport Agency|website=www.nzta.govt.nz|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> and it was opened in March 1923 at a total cost of about \u00a360,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19230331.2.114&srpos=3265&zto=1|title=Link With Taranaxi.|date=1923-03-31|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=10|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> (2016 equivalent $5.8m).<ref name=\":0\" /> Most of the route was gazetted as a government main highway in 1924,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=EP19240613.2.139&srpos=15&zto=1|title=Main Roads|date=1924-06-13|newspaper=Evening Post|pages=10|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> some sections were tar-sealed in 1925<ref name=\"Road To Taranaki\">{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19250507.2.39&srpos=3333&zto=1|title=Road To Taranaki.|date=1925-05-07|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=8|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> and more work had been done on the road by 1936, leaving only a few mud sections.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19361019.2.114&zto=1|title=Better Roads|date=1936-10-19|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=10|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> By 1949 the road was sealed as far south as Te Kuiti and the reinforced concrete bridge over the Waipa at Otorohanga had been started.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://atojs.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/atojs?a=d&d=AJHR1949-I.2.2.3.1&pg=51|title=AtoJs Online \u2014 Appendix to the Journals of the House of Representatives \u2014 1949 Session I  \u2014 D-01 MINISTRY OF WORKS STATEMENT (BY THE HON. R. SEMPLE, MINISTER OF WORKS)|website=atojs.natlib.govt.nz|page=53|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n[[File:Mokau Bridge.jpg|left|thumb|Mokau Bridge opened 1927]]\nThe {{Convert|12|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide, single-lane,<ref name=\"Road To Taranaki\"/> 11-span, {{Convert|670|ft|m|abbr=on}}, steel,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19250706.2.42&srpos=3358&zto=1|title=Mokau River Bridge.|date=1925-07-06|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=8|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> '''Mokau Bridge'''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=NZH19271217.2.44&srpos=3496&zto=1|title=Mokau River Bridge.|date=1927-12-17|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=12|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> opened in October 1927<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=NZH19271017.2.11.7&zto=1|title=Main Highway From Auckland To Taranaki Now Completed: The Mokau River Bridge Open For Traffic Photographs Taken On Friday Last. Left: A View From The Bridge Showing Cars Waiting For The Lift-span In The Middle Of The Structure To Be Lowered. Right: A General View Of The New Bridge, Which Eliminates The Ancient Ferry-punt So Well Known To Travellers On Thete Kuiti-new Plymouth Section Of The Route. The Opening Of The Bridge Will Expedite Overland Travel And Incidentally Enable The New ' ' Zealand Herald To Reach New Plymouth Earlier Every Day.|date=1927-10-17|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|pages=6|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> (official opening 17 December), replacing a [[Cable ferry|punt]]. The cost was \u00a335,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=CHP19271219.2.63&srpos=3498&zto=1|title=Mokau Bridge Opened.|date=1927-12-19|newspaper=Press|pages=10|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> (2016 equivalent $3.3m).<ref name=\":0\" /> It had a lifting span allowing passage of vessels up to {{Convert|50|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide and with a {{Convert|60|ft|m|abbr=on}} clearance at high tide.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2001 the 1927 bridge was replaced by the current 9-span, {{Convert|230|m|yd|abbr=on}}, double lane, [[Prestressed concrete|pre-stressed concrete]] bridge for $6.2m<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smithbridge.net/projects/item/mokau-bridge.html|title=Mokau Bridge \u2013 Smithbridge|website=www.smithbridge.net|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> (2016 equivalent $8.5m).<ref name=\":0\" /> The new bridge doesn't allow for shipping, as the first ship to pass under the old lifting span was withdrawn three months after the bridge opened.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/taranaki-daily-news/news/9381752/The-story-of-the-steamer-Wetere|title=The story of the steamer Wetere|last=Duckett|first=Graeme|date=2013-11-09|newspaper=Stuff.co.nz|language=English|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref>\n\nAn 1871 account of a coach journey from New Plymouth to Wellington described the very poor road round the coast via [[Opunake]] to [[Whanganui]] and the much better and well used road south from there. A government subsidy of \u00a33,000 (2016 equivalent $400,000)<ref name=\":0\" /> a year was being paid for the coach north of Whanganui.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=TH18710802.2.16&srpos=15&zto=1|title=New Plymouth To Wellington\" Overland.|date=1871-08-02|newspaper=Taranaki Herald|pages=2|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref>\n\n==Route==\n[[File:Awakino tunnel.jpg|thumb|left|Tunnel at the north end of the Awakino Gorge. There is another short tunnel near the top of Mount Messenger]]\nThe highway leaves SH 1 at Hamilton, and initially heads south through farmland, passing through [[Te Awamutu]]. Sections of this stretch of the road are four-laned, but not divided carriageway. From [[Otorohanga]] it follows the valley of the [[Waipa River]] to [[Te Kuiti]]. The road then turns southwest through sparsely settled farmland, crossing several ridges before following the Awakino gorge to reach the coast, which it follows around the North Taranaki Bight. At the [[Tongaporutu River]] the highway turns inland to avoid coastal cliffs and climbs over Mount Messenger before descending via the [[Mimi River (New Zealand)|Mimi River]] valley to return to the coast near [[Urenui]]. Bypassing [[Waitara, New Zealand|Waitara]], it reaches [[New Plymouth]] then turns inland, passing to the east of [[Mount Taranaki]] via [[Inglewood, New Zealand|Inglewood]], [[Stratford, New Zealand|Stratford]] and [[Eltham, New Zealand|Eltham]] to [[Hawera]].\n\nFrom Hawera the highway follows the coast of the South Taranaki Bight southeastwards to [[Patea]] and [[Whanganui]] before meeting SH 1 again at [[Bulls, New Zealand|Bulls]]. SH 1 and 3 share their route for 6&nbsp;km as they cross the [[Rangitikei River]] to [[Sanson, New Zealand|Sanson]], where SH 3 continues southeast towards [[Palmerston North]]. After crossing the [[Manawatu River]], the route follows its south bank through the [[Manawatu Gorge]] to its terminus and junction with [[New Zealand State Highway 2|SH 2]] at [[Woodville, New Zealand|Woodville]] in the [[Tararua District]]\n\nBoth the Awakino and Manawatu gorges are prone to closure by slips and rockslides in heavy rain.\n\n==Route changes==\nConstruction of a bypass of [[Bell Block, Taranaki|Bell Block]], a satellite town of New Plymouth, was completed in 2010. The bypass is a four-lane, divided expressway with an interchange at Henwood Road providing access to Bell Block.<ref name=\"Stuff.co.nz_3438349\">{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/taranaki-daily-news/news/3438349/Bypass-ready-to-roll |title=Bypass ready to roll |author=Maetzig, Rob |date=12 March 2010 |work=[[Taranaki Daily News]] |accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, a section of SH 3 in Taranaki was realigned replacing the \"deadly\" [[Normanby, Taranaki|Normanby]] overbridge.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/taranaki-daily-news/news/85389029/normanby-overbridge-bypass-ready-for-use-from-monday |title=Normanby overbridge bypass ready for use from Monday |author=David Burroughs |work=Taranaki Daily News |date=16 October 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Future improvements==\nOn 27 January 2016, funding was announced for road bypasses of the two tunnels north of [[New Plymouth]]. Construction of the Mount Messenger and Awakino Gorge tunnel bypasses was expected to begin within two years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/politics/news/article.cfm?c_id=280&objectid=11580485 |title=Key's state of the nation \u2013 full speech |accessdate=2016-01-27 |publisher=NZHerald.co.nz}}</ref>\n\nState Highway 3 will also form part of the future/proposed Southern Links motorway project in the South/West of Hamilton and Tamahere.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzta.govt.nz/projects/southern-links |title=Southern Links |publisher=NZTA.govt.nz}}</ref>\n\nThe highway through the [[Manawatu Gorge]] between [[Ashhurst]] and [[Woodville, New Zealand|Woodville]] in the [[Manawatu-Wanganui|Manawatu Whanganui Region]] was closed in April 2017 due to a large slip, with SH 3 traffic diverted via Saddle Road. Contractors were pulled out of clearing the slip in July 2017 due to ongoing geological movement in the hill, closing the road indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11887257|title=Manawatu Gorge to remain closed 'for some time'|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2017-07-10|language=en-NZ}}</ref> The NZTA is fast-tracking a long-term solution to bypass and replace the gorge, although it is not expected to be in place before 2023. \n\nOther improvements include:\n*An upgrade of SH 3 in New Plymouth from Vickers Road to the city<ref name=\"Taranakiinvestments\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nzta.govt.nz/planning-and-investment/2015-18-national-land-transport-programme/nltp-in-the-regions/taranaki/#key-routes |title=Taranaki key routes and investments |work=NZ Transport Agency |accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Spur sections==\n{{infobox road small\n|country=NZL\n|type=SH\n|route=3A\n|length_km=15.6\n|length_round=1\n|location=SH 3 west of Waitara \u2013 SH 3 at Inglewood\n}}\nSH 3 has one spur, designated State Highway 3A. This 15.6&nbsp;km stretch links State Highway 3 just west of Waitara to Inglewood, providing a shortcut and bypass of New Plymouth. The entire length of highway carries the name Mountain Road with the sole exception being a very short link of Rata Street in Inglewood to rejoin SH 3.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Major junctions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Territorial authorities of New Zealand|Territorial authority]] !! Location !! km !! jct !! Destinations !! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton City]] || rowspan=2| Melville || 0 || [[File:New Zealand road sign W10-4.svg|25px]] || {{jct|country=NZL|SH|1|dir1=north|name1=Kahikatea Drive}} \u2013 [[Auckland]]<br>{{jct|country=NZL|SH|1|dir1=south|name1=Lorne Street}} \u2013 [[Rotorua]], [[Taupo]] || ''SH 3 begins''\n|-\n| 1 || [[File:New Zealand road sign W11-1.svg|25px]] || Normandy Ave \u2013 [[Hamilton, New Zealand|City Centre]], [[Rotorua]] || to {{jct|country=NZL|SH|1}}/[[Thermal Explorer Highway]] south\n|-\n| [[Waipa District]] || [[Hamilton Airport (New Zealand)|Hamilton Airport]] || 10 || [[